<HEAD>Jury: Joey Heatherton Did Not Assault Clerk</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A jury ruled Friday that <PERSON> Joey </PERSON> <PERSON> Heatherton </PERSON> was negligent but did not assault or beat a passport clerk who claimed the entertainer attacked her in 1985, and both women said they were pleased with the verdict. The jury refused to award any money for pain and suffering, emotional distress or punitive damages, but it assessed Miss <PERSON> Heatherton </PERSON> $ 20,500 for the year's salary the clerk lost and her medical bills. <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Polik </PERSON> sued <PERSON> Miss </PERSON> <PERSON> Heatherton </PERSON>, 44, for $ 6 million, claiming that the entertainer ripped out her hair, slapped her and `` banged and bashed'' her head on a counter top after she told her she had the wrong photos for a passport and that she needed the $ 35 fee in exact change. `` I'm very happy,'' <PERSON> Heatherton </PERSON> said. `` I've been vindicated and I'm glad the situation has been resolved.'' `` Ms. <PERSON> Polik </PERSON> was looking for a $ 6 million gold mine and instead she's back to where she was in 1985 _ working for a living like everybody else,'' added <PERSON> Heatherton </PERSON>'s attorney, <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Kunstler </PERSON>. <PERSON> Polik </PERSON> also said she was pleased with the verdict. `` No human being has the right to beat up on another,'' she said. <PERSON> Polik </PERSON>'s lawyer, <PERSON> Marie </PERSON> <PERSON> Ng </PERSON>, said she considered the verdict a victory for Polik. `` I am thrilled,'' she said. `` The jury found Ms. <PERSON> Heatherton </PERSON> negligent. They said that intentionally or unintentionally she did what she was accused of and ordered her to pay for medical expenses and loss of earnings.'' <PERSON> Polik </PERSON>, 27, said she suffered pinched neck nerves, headaches, dizziness and nausea following the July 8, 1985, attack.
