<FIRST>r i PM-China-Army     06-24 0846</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Army,0868</SECOND>
<HEAD>Army to Continue Playing Key Role on Political Scene</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>, which crushed <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s pro-democracy movement, is expected to play an increasingly important role in civilian politics. It was lack of army support that doomed Communist Party General Secretary <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> <PERSON> Ziyang </PERSON> when he challenged senior leader <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> <PERSON> Xiaoping </PERSON>'s condemnation of student protesters for a freer society. Now that at least 150,000 soldiers are stationed in and around <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> to enforce martial law, cultivating the army will be a necessity for any replacement for <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> and prospective successor to the 84-year-old <PERSON> Deng </PERSON>. Which way the army will throw its support and whether it will stand united behind one candidate have become key questions, but most foreign diplomats and military experts say they can do little more than guess. One problem is that normal diplomatic and military contacts have been interrupted by the fighting in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>. Outsiders have been reduced to watching which generals appear on television and reading between the lines in their speeches. Another is that the military stands outside the political dichotomy of liberals and conservatives defined by their stands on the speed of economic reform and degree of cultural freedom. The military has its own priorities, including stability and maintaining a political atmosphere in which the army has high status. Political initiatives are unlikely to come from the rank and file, many of whom are illiterate and subjected to heavy propaganda. Young officers with relatively liberal educations might support reformers such as <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> but have little power. The key players will be senior officers in their 50s and 60s who owe their positions to <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> and are desirous of promotion and national stability. By and large, the conservatives seem to meet their interests best right now, although long-term stability under a leadership that continues to repress the citizenry is dubious. In the latest move, army propaganda chief <PERSON> Shao </PERSON> <PERSON> Huaze </PERSON> took over as editor in chief of the party's official newspaper, the People's Daily The paper said today that <PERSON> Shao </PERSON> replaced <PERSON> Tan </PERSON> <PERSON> Wenrui </PERSON>, who resigned for health reasons. <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON>'s problems with the military began well before weeks of student protests for which he expressed sympathy threw the party leadership into crisis. <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> was part of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s rising `` young'' generation of leaders in their 50s and 60s who, unlike <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> and those in their 80s, were not army officers in the pre-1949 civil war and World War II. Their rise was interpreted as part of a natural evolution from the heavily ideological politics of a revolutionary leadeship toward a more pragmatic and even technocratic government style. But the status and budget of the military eroded steadily under the new leaders as funds were shifted from defense to economic development. <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> approved the shift, but it appears <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> took the blame. <PERSON> Deng </PERSON>'s personal power base was in the <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>, in which he served as political commissar during the 1930s and 1940s when it fought the Nationalist government and Japanese invaders. He made <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> a vice chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Military </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, which he heads and which sets military policy. The army reportedly remained lukewarm toward <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON>, who was more comfortable meeting diplomats and playing golf than visiting the troops. When <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> cast his vote against a crackdown on the protesters and publicly blamed the growing chaos on <PERSON> Deng </PERSON>, not one army official rose to <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON>'s support, according to foreign diplomats. There clearly was opposition to orders to shoot the crowd protecting the students. Some units sat on the sidelines throughout the battling and never joined in. There were reports, never confirmed, of individual soldiers or small groups firing on other soldiers who shot civilians. But there were no reports of units opposing the political shakeup or contemplating an anti-Deng coup. Clues in the official media indicate <PERSON> Deng </PERSON>'s candidate to succeed <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> is <PERSON> Qiao </PERSON> <PERSON> Shi </PERSON>, a member of the party's top decision-making group. He also lacks a military background, but he may have an alternative acceptable to the senior officers: he is believed in charge of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s internal secret service, and at one point was reported to oversee the people's armed police, which has links to the army. There are no indications the army is preparing to throw up its own candidate. The military has not put forward a political candidate since Marshal <PERSON> Lin </PERSON> <PERSON> Piao </PERSON> fell from grace as <PERSON> Mao </PERSON> <PERSON> Tse-tung </PERSON>'s prospective heir in 1971 after allegedly plotting a coup One lesson may be drawn from the army's performance of the past few weeks. Even in the face of the hardest choice many soldiers probably have ever had to make _ to disobey orders or to shoot at people who had been giving them drinks and food for days as they sat parked in trucks around <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> _ discipline and unity prevailed. When it comes time to rally behind a successor to <PERSON> Deng </PERSON>, the army likely will act as one.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Kathy </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilhelm </PERSON> has reported from <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> for The Associated Press for two years.
</TEXT>
