<HEAD>Memo Stirs Flap over City Councilman's Overalls</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHWOOD, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A pair of worn, faded overalls has caused a flap at City Hall where the mayor wants a councilman to pay more attention to his appearance. After Councilman <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> <PERSON> McKnight </PERSON> showed up recently at a <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> workshop in overalls, Mayor <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Head </PERSON> issued a memo asking councilmen to dress properly when representing <LOCATION> Richwood </LOCATION>, a small town about 50 miles south of <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>. The memo mentions no names, but <PERSON> Head </PERSON> said it was directed at <PERSON> McKnight </PERSON>. His memo does not ban jeans but asks that they be clean and in good shape. `` While I'm sure that faded overalls and T-shirts are comfortable, I feel that they have no place in the council chambers,'' Head wrote. `` Hell will freeze over before I let anyone tell me how to dress,'' <PERSON> McKnight </PERSON> said. `` It's nobody's business how a person dresses. If someone wants to come down there in rags, that's his business.'' He intends to wear his overalls to the July 11 council meeting. <PERSON> McKnight </PERSON>, 54, said he has only worn overalls once since being elected in May, and that was because he did n't have time to change after taking care of some goats at his farm. But <PERSON> Head </PERSON> said <PERSON> McKnight </PERSON> has shown up at City Hall wearing T-shirts with holes around the neck, and cares little about his appearance when representing the city. <PERSON> McKnight </PERSON> lost an election to Head in 1988 but won a council post by a slim margin as a write-in candidate in May. Head, 50, stepped down from his council post to run unopposed for mayor in May.
