 A disgruntled customer has been accused of staging a one-man demolition derby at a suburban <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION> car dealership. Police said <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> `` Pete'' <PERSON> Ruff </PERSON>, 72, drove a 1989 Toyota through the glass doors of <ORGANIZATION> Krebs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Toyota </ORGANIZATION>'s showroom in <LOCATION> Shaler </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Township </LOCATION> on June 15 and crashed into five vehicles, including a police cruiser called to the scene. He caused about $ 5,000 damage, authorities said. The dispute was related to a car <PERSON> Ruff </PERSON> had leased from <PERSON> Krebs </PERSON>, according to <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Kay </PERSON> <PERSON> Condie </PERSON>, District Justice <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Bowen </PERSON>'s secretary `` He apparently found out that he could have got a better deal by buying the car,'' she said after the retiree's arraignment Wednesday. <PERSON> Ruff </PERSON> has been charged with reckless endangerment, criminal mischief, simple assault, terroristic threats and resisting arrest. The criminal complaint against <PERSON> Ruff </PERSON> alleges he threatened dealership salesmen `` with bodily harm.''
