<FIRST>r w PM-ChildCare Bjt   06-24 0626</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Child Care, Bjt,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Passes Child Care Bill; Fight Shifts To House</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> passage of an unprecedented child-care package sends the debate to the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, where Republicans and the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration promise to fight anew for a plan without the billion-dollar subsidies being pushed by Democrats. `` We've made a significant step toward providing affordable, safe care for <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> children and equal economic opportunity for <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> women,'' <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Majority Leader <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Maine </LOCATION>, said Friday just before the measure passed on a voice vote. With $ 1.75 billion in direct subsidies for the fiscal year beginning Oct. 1 and more than $ 2 billion a year in tax credits, the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> package represents the greatest government effort ever to address child-care needs of working parents and its first major effort since an emergency plan adopted during World War II. Action on child care is expected to accelerate in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> next week, and Republicans vowed to fight for legislation far different from the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>'s plan. `` This is just a first step and a very short step,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Republican leader <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION>. `` I'm going to encourage the administration not to view what happened in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> as final.'' With the White House raising the possibility of a veto, Democrats too said they hoped to strike a compromise, although they are not willing to abandon the subsidy approach. `` We are quite willing to hear the administration, to listen to their suggestions and their recommendations,'' said Sen. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, D-Mass. It appeared early Friday that partisan bickering would threaten a two-week <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> recess. But Republicans, after losing several attempts to significantly change the Democratic bill, relented and struck a deal with majority Democrats on a timetable to end the debate. Only a handful of senators remained when the measure passed. The leadership had agreed to the voice vote so those lawmakers who had to catch flights out of <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> would not be recorded as absent for the vote. Democrats characterized the legislation as historic and a long-overdue effort to support low-income parents who must work but can not find affordable child care. `` The real winners, the children, are closer to a safer, more effective and affordable child-care program,'' said <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>. The measure was the product of an unusual alliance between liberal Democrat <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Dodd </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION> Republican <PERSON> Orrin </PERSON> <PERSON> Hatch </PERSON>, whose conservative credentials helped Democrats brush aside many <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> attacks on the plan. `` This is a monumental achievement,'' <PERSON> Hatch </PERSON> said. Despite changes designed to accommodate <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> said the measure contained `` nothing for the president of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> added that despite the addition of provisions <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> favored, the bill remained `` a candidate for a veto.'' In addition to the $ 1.75 billion authorization for child-care subsidies, the measure includes three tax-relief provisions designed to help low - and moderate-income families pay for child care and health insurance for their children One would supplement the existing Earned Income Tax Credit to provide up to $ 750 more for parents whose annual incomes are less than $ 10,000 and have two or more children under age 5. Parents could receive a $ 500 credit for one eligible child. The second tax-related provision allows those who qualify for the existing Dependent Care Tax Credit to get 90 percent of their credit up front, a move designed to give cash to families who are eligible for the credit but can not take advantage of it because they do n't make enough to owe federal taxes The third provision, which Republicans vigorously opposed, would provide parents with annual incomes of less than $ 12,000 with a tax credit of to $ 500 to pay 50 percent of the cost of buying health insurance for their children.
