<DATELINE>KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Inquiries about the sale of the Malayan Railway for 37 cents continue to pour in from abroad, the transport ministry said today. The minister, <PERSON> Ling </PERSON> <PERSON> Liong </PERSON> <PERSON> Sik </PERSON>, told reporters no decision has been made on a buyer of the railway because the government Economic Planning Unit was still evaluating recommendations by <ORGANIZATION> Bumiputra </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Merchant </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> on the privatization of the railway. There are no private railways in <LOCATION> Malaysia </LOCATION>. Officials said Japanese, Canadians and Americans were among those who were serious about buying the railway, which has about 1,000 miles of track and hundreds of millions of dollars worth of assets, including its rolling stock, land, buildings and trucks. It also has debts of about $ 407 million. Eighteen months ago, the government announced it planned to sell the <ORGANIZATION> Malayan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Railway </ORGANIZATION> for one ringgit, or 37 cents, as part of plans to privatize many state companies, including <ORGANIZATION> Malaysia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Telecommuncations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, ports and the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electricity </ORGANIZATION> board.
