<HEAD>Damaged Tanker Heads for California</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Oil Spill, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL JENKINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VALDEZ, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The battered tanker <PERSON> Exxon </PERSON> <PERSON> Valdez </PERSON> was pulled cautiously toward <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> today, leaving behind stained shorelines and angry feelings from the nation's worst oil spill. `` I must say we're not sorry to see it go,'' Gov. <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Cowper </PERSON> said at a news conference in <LOCATION> Juneau </LOCATION>. The 987-foot vessel was stopped briefly for a scheduled look at its hull, and video cameras were used to ensure that the punctured hull was sound before the damaged ship was towed into the often stormy Gulf of <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> en route to a <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION> drydock and more than $ 25 million in repairs. The 2,500-mile trip is expected to take about 20 days. The Exxon Valdez rammed <LOCATION> Bligh </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Reef </LOCATION> on March 24, dumping almost 11 million gallons of heavy North Slope crude oil into the waters of Prince <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Sound </PERSON>. After the accident, authorities pumped the remaining oil from the ship into other tankers. The spill killed thousands of birds and sea mammals and spoiled hundreds of miles of coastline. It also dealt a severe blow to <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>'s $ 2 billion fishing industry, forcing officials to ban, postpone or restrict fishing. The vessel unceremoniously lifted anchor Friday and came under tow behind two 7,000-horsepower ocean-going tugboats. A third tug was attached to the tanker's stern. A salvage boat trailed not far behind. Two escort vessels loaded with 9,000 feet of containment boom and each carrying an oil skimming vessel with 4,000 barrels' capacity brought up the rear. <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Kapp </PERSON>, skipper of the Journeyman out of <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, posted a hand-lettered sign on the side of his boat as he ushered the Exxon Valdez away. `` Thanks a lot Exxon,'' the sign said. Speaking by radio to a nearby media vessel, <PERSON> Kapp </PERSON> said fishing closures have hurt: `` It's disrupted my life; it's disrupted our industry.'' Progress initially was slow, and the tanker moved only about two miles in the first two hours, said <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Beathard </PERSON>. The speed is expected to increase to about 5 mph. <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Brenda </PERSON> <PERSON> Toledo </PERSON> said a light film of oil was reported on the water near the tanker as it got under way. The source of the sheen was unclear, she said, adding not much oil is necessary to make a sheen. `` We're talking pints, not gallons,'' she said. Seven Exxon officers and four salvage experts were aboard for the trip to <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION>, officials said. The skeleton crew will monitor air pressure in the vessel's cargo tanks, conduct inspections and be ready to help with the ship's engines should the vessel run into trouble <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Alyeska </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pipeline </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> have been criticized for their slow handling of the spill during its first few days. Today, oil with a sludge-like consistency can be found 700 miles from the reef. The tanker's former captain, <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Hazelwood </PERSON>, has pleaded innocent to three felony counts of criminal mischief and misdemeanors, including negligent discharge of pollutants and operating a vessel while drunk. He is free on $ 50,000 bail.
