<HEAD>Outgoing Social Security Chief Says Public Confidence Restored</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Dorcas </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hardy </PERSON> says she is stepping down as head of Social Security satisfied the agency she modernized and streamlined, sometimes in the face of sharp congressional criticism, is in good shape. But she warns that while overall public confidence in the program is justifiably high, policies using Social Security Trust Funds to underwrite other government programs and reduce the federal budget deficit are `` fueling a lack of confidence'' in the program by younger workers. `` Social Security continues to be misunderstood, by beneficiaries, taxpayers and elected officials alike, and most younger workers do not trust that the government will preserve Social Security for their ` Golden Years,''' she said in her letter of resignation to President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> on Friday. <PERSON> Hardy </PERSON> said she has confidence in the future of the Social Security program, `` but that's not to say everybody does.'' And, she said, many workers are `` discouraged'' by a provision covering the working elderly that withholds $ 1 for every $ 2 they earn over $ 8,880 a year, a provision she has worked to repeal. <PERSON> Hardy </PERSON>, 42, had sought to remain in the <LOCATION> Social </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Security </LOCATION> post she has held for three years, but told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration indicated to her she would be replaced. The administration is expected to nominate <PERSON> Gwendolyn </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON>, a former legislative aide to Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Heinz </PERSON>, R-Pa., who later headed the office of Attorney General <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> when he was governor of <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>, according to sources who spoke on the condition of anonymity <PERSON> Hardy </PERSON> said she will leave July 31, and plans to host a weekly, syndicated television program about finances and explore other options in the private sector. <PERSON> Hardy </PERSON>'s tenure was marked by efforts to streamline and modernize the agency despite declines in staffing, but critics on <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> said service at the agency has deteriorated. Among the criticisms against her was that new services she introduced have been implemented poorly and resulted in worse service to the public. For example, a toll-free telephone service to provide information to individuals on their benefits has come under fire for a high rate of busy signals and inaccurate information is given to callers. A <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> committee earlier this year asked whether Social Security was violating privacy rights through its practice, since halted, of verifying millions of Social Security numbers for private companies engaged in checking credit ratings. And a House Government Operations subcommittee in March began an inquiry into whether <PERSON> Hardy </PERSON> combined business trips with vacations and political campaigning for members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. Sen. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Pryor </PERSON>, D-Ark., chairman of the Special <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> on Aging and one of <PERSON> Hardy </PERSON>'s harshest critics in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, said he hoped new leadership `` can recapture the original spirit of the agency to provide compassionate service to our most vulnerable citizens. But <PERSON> Hardy </PERSON> said the agency now has a plan that will lead a solvent trust fund into the next century, and `` the vast majority of the public is very pleased with the service Social Security provides.'' A trust fund that was considered shaky before she took office now has enough money to pay benefits until at least the middle of the next century, according to a <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> report in April. She takes credit for modernizing the agency's massive computer operations, launching the 800 telephone service and providing to all workers Social Security benefit estimates upon request. `` All this has been accomplished despite an imposed 20 percent decrease in staffing,'' in which 63,000 jobs were eliminated through attrition, she said. When she was named to head Social Security by President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> in 1986, she became the first woman to head the agency. She worked for <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> on welfare issues when he was governor of <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, and she was an assistant secretary at the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> during his first presidential term before being named to the Social Security post.
