<HEAD>NHTSA Releases New Crash-Test Results</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Federal engineers say crash tests of 19 cars show drivers of the Chevrolet Astro Van have the greatest chance of head injury in an accident. The van's manufacturer, <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, said the federal tests are n't a valid indicator of crash-worthiness. The Astro Van was among 12 vehicles listed in the third round of crash-test results released Friday by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Highway </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Traffic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>. The vehicles were tested under <ORGANIZATION> NHTSA </ORGANIZATION>'s program to provide consumers a guide to the safety of 1989 vehicles Results of seven other vehicles had been released previously. <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> said the federal test results `` do not reflect the actual safety performance of these vehicles on the road'' because the test is done on only one vehicle. The vehicles were smashed at 35 mph into a fixed barrier, and the stresses that resulted were measured by sensors on human-shaped dummies protected by seat belts or other crash-protection devices. <ORGANIZATION> NHTSA </ORGANIZATION> engineers reported stresses on the head as an index called the head injury criterion. The higher the index, the greater the likelihood of injury. The Astro Van crash test produced a head injury criterion of 1,849 for the driver-side dummy in the Astro Van, <ORGANIZATION> NHTSA </ORGANIZATION> said. The figure was more than double the head injury criterion recorded in a test of the <ORGANIZATION> Mitsubishi </ORGANIZATION> van, the only other van tested this year. The <ORGANIZATION> Mitsubishi </ORGANIZATION> had a head injury criterion of 805, <ORGANIZATION> NHTSA </ORGANIZATION> said. Federal regulations require cars on the market to produce a head injury criterion no greater than 1,000 in tests conducted by the automakers. The public tests done by <ORGANIZATION> NHTSA </ORGANIZATION> and the mandatory tests to meet safety regulations are not considered comparable because the automakers' tests are done at 30 mph. Other new test results by weight class produced these driver head injury criteria: _ Subcompact cars: Mercury Tracer 4-door hatchback, 940 _ Compact cars: <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> Probe 2-door hatchback, 970 _ Large and mid-size cars: Chevrolet Caprice 4-door sedan, 1,328; <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> Fifth Avenue 4-door sedan, 786; Eagle Premier 4-door sedan, 877; <ORGANIZATION> Lincoln </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> 4-door sedan, 863; and <ORGANIZATION> Plymouth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Acclaim </ORGANIZATION> 4-door sedan, 663 _ Trucks, vans and multi-purpose vehicles: Chevrolet S-10 Blazer, 834; <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bronco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> II </ORGANIZATION>, 994; and Jeep Cherokee, 968 <ORGANIZATION> NHTSA </ORGANIZATION> said small differences in test results are n't considered significant. Previously released test results, by weight class, were: _ Subcompact: <LOCATION> Dodge </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Daytona </LOCATION> 2-door hatchback, 399; <ORGANIZATION> Honda </ORGANIZATION> Civic CRX 2-door hatchback, 750; <ORGANIZATION> Mitsubishi </ORGANIZATION> Mirage 4-door sedan, 960 _ Compact: <ORGANIZATION> Mitsubishi </ORGANIZATION> Galant 4-door sedan, 971 _ Large and mid-size: <ORGANIZATION> Dodge </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Spirit </ORGANIZATION> 4-door sedan, 1,421; Eagle Medallion 4-door sedan, 745; Ford Thunderbird 2-door, 541
