<HEAD>Activists Vow New Fight For Civil Rights Legislation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENISE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Activists commemorated the murders 25 years ago of three young civil rights workers by vowing to fight in their spirit to strengthen voter registration and reverse the effects of <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> decisions on affirmative action. But relatives of the slain workers said they were disappointed President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> did not commit himself to new civil rights legislation. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> told family members of <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Schwerner </PERSON> and <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Goodman </PERSON>, both white New Yorkers, and <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Chaney </PERSON>, a black Mississippian, that the men killed by <PERSON> Ku </PERSON> <PERSON> Klux </PERSON> <PERSON> Klansmen </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Miss. </LOCATION>, were `` heroes.'' `` We can erect no greater monument to their memory than to ensure that the arrogance and bigotry that took their lives never again exists in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said in a statement released at the White House. White House spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said the president is waiting for a <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> review of the new <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> rulings before making any commitment to action. The families were on a bus caravan from <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Miss. </LOCATION>, to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> to commemorate the June 21, 1964 disappearance of the men, who had been conducting a black voter registration drive in <LOCATION> Neshoba </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>. Their bullet-riddled bodies were found buried in an earthen dam near <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Miss. </LOCATION>, and the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> found that the <PERSON> Ku </PERSON> <PERSON> Klux </PERSON> <PERSON> Klan </PERSON> had killed them. <PERSON> Rita </PERSON> <PERSON> Schwerner-Bender </PERSON>, who was married to <PERSON> Schwerner </PERSON>, told reporters she was disappointed <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was noncommittal when they asked him to back bipartisan legislation `` to deal with the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> cases that have so badly eroded civil rights in this country.'' At a ceremony at the Capitol, she charged the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> stand in the way of `` a suitable and fitting memorial'' to those who participated in the civil rights struggle. `` So long as the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> argues before the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> for a narrowing of the laws ... so long as the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and the president fail to commit themselves to the needs of the poor, housing, education, medical assistance there is no honor shown to the civil rights participants,'' she said. <PERSON> Ben </PERSON> <PERSON> Chaney </PERSON>, brother of the slain <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Chaney </PERSON>, told about 300 people in the Capitol's Statuary Hall, `` We have to remember they did n't volunteer to die.'' `` We need immediate passage of federal legislation that eliminates all the barriers to voting,'' <PERSON> Chaney </PERSON> said. `` This present majority on the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> is far more dangerous than <PERSON> Bull </PERSON> <PERSON> Connor </PERSON> with a fire hose,'' said <PERSON> Benjamin </PERSON> <PERSON> Hooks </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> NAACP </ORGANIZATION>, referring to the <LOCATION> Birmingham </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ala. </LOCATION>, city official's actions against civil rights demonstrators. Hooks also vowed legislative remedies to reverse <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> rulings. Or, `` we'll have demonstrations that'll make what happen in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> look like child's play,'' he said, raising the threat of thousands of protestors converging on the capital.
