<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> is taking action to stop airline manufacturers from placing exit doors too far apart. The Association of Flight Attendants praised Friday's order, which limits doors to within 60 feet apart, saying it will stop <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> plans to remove middle doors over the wings of future jumbo jets. But a <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> spokesman in <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>, <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Jimenez </PERSON>, said the aircraft builder already has abandoned any plans that would put exit doors in its planes further than 60 feet apart. The <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> said its order will `` hold the line'' on the growth of distances between airliner exit doors, noting that one unidentified model was planned with exits more than 80 feet apart. The new regulations published in Friday's edition of the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Register </ORGANIZATION> take effect in 30 days and apply to `` all newly manufactured airplanes of older type designs after Oct. 16, 1987,'' when the rule was first proposed, the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> said. The rule also will prevent any modification of existing designs that would increase the distance between doors beyond 60 feet and prohibit <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> airlines from using foreign airplanes that have exit distances exceeding the new standard, the agency said. The <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> said it is forming an advisory committee to set standards based on how quickly passengers can exit from the doors rather than on arbitrary distances between doors. The committee is to make recommendations by July 1991. The flight attendants group, in a prepared statement, said <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION>'s plans would have created a 72-foot distance between some of the plane's exit doors. The association had urged <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to save 747 exits over the wing, saying `` passengers in many crashes have been unable to reach exits in post-crash fires.'' <PERSON> Jimenez </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> had planned to remove two of the 10 exit doors on new 747s but abandoned the plan prior to the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> order. He said the new order would not affect any <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> model. Previous <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> rules have required require at least one exit door for every 55 seats. The <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> said all narrow-body airplanes and most wide-body planes already conform to the new distance limit.
