<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, angered over this week's <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruling that burning the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> flag is constitutionally protected free speech, passed legislation aimed at making desecration of the flag unlawful. Sen. <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Biden </PERSON>, D-Del., had the measure tacked onto an unrelated child care bill late Friday `` I'm confident it's constitutional,'' <PERSON> Biden </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Judiciary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> and a leading congressional liberal, told his colleagues. The move in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> came as several lawmakers introduced constitutional amendments in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> following the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> decision. House Speaker <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Foley </PERSON>, D-Wash., said such attempts should be taken cautiously and that it would `` be extraordinarily slow to amend the First Amendment to the Constitution,'' which is `` at the heart of our constitutional liberties and freedom. <PERSON> Biden </PERSON> said his simple legislation could accomplish the same aim as a constitutional amendment. The bill reads: `` Whoever knowingly and publicly mutilates, defaces, burns, displays on the floor or ground, or tramples upon any flag of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> shall be fined not more than $ 1,000 or imprisoned for not more than one year, or both.'' <PERSON> Biden </PERSON>'s bill is identical to the federal statute on flag desecration except it removes the words `` cast contempt.'' The majority <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> opinion reasoned that a <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> statute on flag desecration violated the First Amendment because it was aimed at protecting against acts toward the flag which would be offensive to others. <PERSON> Biden </PERSON>'s measure would treat desecration as an act of vandalism without considering whether anyone was offended by the act, presumably answering the court's First Amendment concerns. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> may consider next week a resolution similar to the one passed by the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> this week expressing opposition to the view of the court. Rep. <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Hyde </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, a senior Republican on the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Judiciary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, said he was also exploring ways of getting around the decision without a constitutional amendment, possibly by taking away from the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> jurisdiction over lawsuits on flag desecration. `` I think the mood of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> is to do something effective and not just pass resolutions condemning the burning of the flag,'' he said. A new law would be simpler than a constitutional amendment, he said.
