<FIRST>r a PM-DropoutCure     06-24 0586</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dropout Cure,0604</SECOND>
<HEAD>Quincy, Mass., Halves Dropout Rate by Tailoring School to Students'
Needs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARLENE LEVINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>QUINCY, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dropout rate was halved after this <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> suburb's officials lavished attention on potential dropouts, offering day-care centers, vocational training for the disabled and night classes for working teens. `` The secret is, a kid ca n't drop out without going through a long program of help-providers,'' said Schools Superintendent <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Ricci </PERSON> on Friday. `` It's nothing that has n't been done. But most districts are n't that flexible. There's a blueprint here for urban districts.'' <PERSON> Ricci </PERSON> calculated the dropout rate by following a group of students from ninth grade through the day they should graduate. The traditional method is to compare senior classes from year to year. By tracking ninth-graders, the schools can more accurately assess whether programs are working, experts said. In <PERSON> Quincy </PERSON>, they apparently work. The 1987-88 class graduating lost 19.7 percent of its students. This year's graduating class was down by just 10.9 percent, a loss of 70 students out of 643 potential graduates. The success in retaining students came from a simple formula. Said <PERSON> Ricci </PERSON>: `` They get a lot of attention and a lot of alternatives.'' Any eighth-graders thought to be potential dropouts receive special counseling to help them make the transition to high school. This is followed up through their ninth grade school year. Potential dropouts are usually a year or more older than their classmates; behind in basic skill levels; or from families that are poorly educated, school officials said. <PERSON> Quincy </PERSON> offers schooling for teen-age mothers by providing day care for their babies, and vocational training for the disabled. The school schedule can be adjusted to the student's needs, including part-time work combined with courses for credit at a junior college or in <LOCATION> Cambridge </LOCATION> at the <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> extension program. Students can work during the day and study for a general equivalency diploma, or a GED, at night. If these inducements do n't work, and a student is determined to drop out, he is encouraged to take the GED exam. If he passes, he can receive his diploma on graduation day. If not, he can take courses to help him pass. <PERSON> Quincy </PERSON> is a largely blue-collar city of 89,000 people just south of <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>. Its public schools serve 8,000 youngsters. The district consists of two high schools and one vocational school. The program was developed through policy changes and some reorginzation, resulting in no significant budget increase. The Quincy results drew applause Friday from others concerned with dropout prevention. <ORGANIZATION> Brandeis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> professor <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Hahn </PERSON>, a labor market specialist concerned with the problems of urban education, praised the Quincy program. `` The dropout problem is something a lot of people are dealing with. When you lose half your ninth-grade class in some of our nation's largest cities, your community is going to suffer,'' <PERSON> Hahn </PERSON> said. `` The best drop-out prevention program has the top administrators involved. What is so notable -LRB- about <PERSON> Quincy </PERSON> -RRB- is that the superintendent is so passionate about it.'' In major cities the attrition rate can be 40 percent to 60 percent, school officials said. Halving a dropout rate is impressive, said <PERSON> Michele </PERSON> <PERSON> Cahill </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Educational </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION>, an international educational consulting firm in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> that works with more than 40 urban school districts on dropout prevention. `` What it seems like they're doing, that they've put in a really good exit intervention,'' Ms. <PERSON> Cahill </PERSON> said. She said researchers are finding that it's the `` comprehensive'' programs that work.
</TEXT>
