<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> <PERSON> Ziyang </PERSON> moved into the political spotlight as a disciple of senior leader <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> <PERSON> Xiaoping </PERSON>, successfully installing economic reforms in <LOCATION> Sichuan </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Province </LOCATION> and bringing a progressive style to the Chinese leadership. But with his ouster today as general secretary of the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> ended up with the same fate as his predecessor _ stripped of power and disgraced for sympathizing with students seeking democratic reforms. In his tailored Western suits, <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> once represented the emergence of a new brand of leader in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, a change from the revolutionary heroes who founded the communist state in 1949 to a new generation showing more interest in economic results than Marxist ideology. <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON>, 69, took over as acting <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> chief in January 1987 after the ouster of <PERSON> Hu </PERSON> <PERSON> Yaobang </PERSON>, who also was considered too sympathetic to student protesters calling for political reforms. Nine months later, <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> formally was named party chief. Hu's death on April 15 set off the student demonstrations in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>. Now <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> too has fallen from favor after showing support for some of the demands of students and opposing the decision to declare martial law in the capital. <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> has not been seen in public since May 19, a day before martial law was imposed. While tens of thousands of students occupied <LOCATION> Tiananmen </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Square </LOCATION> last month, <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> told visiting Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> that <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> people could enjoy `` genuine democracy'' under the 47 million-member <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. He also said political and economic reform should proceed at an equal pace. Like <PERSON> Deng </PERSON>, <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> was purged during the 1966-76 Cultural Revolution, accused of being a capitalist sympathizer. In 1967 he was dragged from his home in the southern city of <LOCATION> Canton </LOCATION> -LRB- <LOCATION> Guangzhou </LOCATION> -RRB- and paraded through the streets with a dunce cap on his head. But he came out of the internal exile that followed to energetically carry out <PERSON> Deng </PERSON>'s market-oriented reforms, measures designed to rebuild and modernize a country that had fallen apart during the extreme leftism and repression of the Cultural Revolution. In 1975, <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> became governor of <LOCATION> Sichuan </LOCATION>, the country's most populous province. He dismantled communes and allowed peasants to till private plots. The reforms ended food shortages that had people at the brink of starvation. Under <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON>, the central province harvested bumper yields. <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> brought <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> to <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> in 1980 as a member of the party's policy-making Politburo and vice premier Six months later be became premier and served in that post until picked to head the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. He traveled widely throughout the world and earned a reputation as an urbane and self-assured <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> leader who was tough at the negotiating table. <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> was born in October 1919, the son of a wealthy landowner in central <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Henan </LOCATION> province. As with most Chinese leaders, few details of his family life are known. He has been married twice and has four sons and a daughter, <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> <PERSON> Liang </PERSON>, who studied in <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION> in 1981-83. He told reporters that he worked 10 hours a day, jogged in the morning and argued with his family at the dinner table. He also regularly played golf, a sport once condemned in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> as a luxury. <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> joined the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Youth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> in 1932 and became a full party member in 1936, 13 years before the communists came to power after chasing the Chinese Nationalists from the mainland. He headed the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> in his native county for most of the 1937-45 war between <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. While serving as a regional party official in the 1950's, he orchestrated a purge in southern <LOCATION> Guangdong </LOCATION> province against cadres accused of corruption, ties to Nationalist <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> and opposition to land reform. In 1957, <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> oversaw a `` rectification'' campaign in which 80,000 officials were banished to the countryside, where they worked and faced criticism for their past actions. <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> disappeared for four years after being purged at the start of the Cultural Revolution, finally re-emerging as party secretary in Inner <LOCATION> Mongolia </LOCATION> in 1971. Duing those chaotic years, he appeared opportunistic. At one point, he called for exposure of <PERSON> Deng </PERSON>'s alleged crimes in an apparent act of self-preservation not uncommon in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s tumultuous politics. By the time <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> reappeared and consolidated power in 1978, <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> was firmly tied to the reformers. `` We must not bind ourselves as silkworms do within cocoons,'' he said in a 1979 speech. `` All economic patterns and conventions which hold back the development of productive forces should be abolished.''
