<HEAD>Communist Party Chief Zhao Stripped of Posts, Shanghai Chief Named</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to ADD quotes from communique, other details. No
pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> today ousted party chief <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> <PERSON> Ziyang </PERSON>, blaming him for the turmoil caused by the pro-democracy movement and for dividing the party. <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON>, 69, an architect of a decade of economic reform, was replaced by <PERSON> Jiang </PERSON> <PERSON> Zemin </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION> party leader who cracked down on demonstrations in his city. <PERSON> Jiang </PERSON> is also considered an advocate of economic modernization. The replacement of <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> as general secretary of the 47-million member party was announced in a communique by the official <ORGANIZATION> Xinhua </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>. A change in party leadership had been rumored since the military assault in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> on June 3-4 left hundreds and perhaps thousands of pro-democracy supporters dead. <PERSON> Jiang </PERSON> has taken a hard line in dealing with the protests since then. He moved swiftly to end large protests that broke out in <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION>, and three men were executed last week in <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION> for participating in riots. A total of 27 people have been executed nationwide. <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> is believed to have been purged for opposing senior leader <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> <PERSON> Xiaoping </PERSON>'s use of troops to quell student protests in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> has not been seen in public since May 19, and his whereabouts were unknown today. The communique, issued after a plenary session of 276 regular and alternate members of the party's <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, said <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> had `` unshirkable responsibilities'' for the recent political turmoil stemming from huge pro-democracy demonstrations in the capital and many other Chinese cities. It accused <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> of supporting the turmoil and `` splitting the party.'' It said <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> caused `` serious losses to the cause of the party.'' The report on <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> was read by Premier <PERSON> Li </PERSON> <PERSON> Peng </PERSON>, the conservative who triumphed over <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> in a party power struggle stemming from the protests. The communique said <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> was dismissed as general secretary, from his post in the 17-member ruling Politburo and its <ORGANIZATION> Standing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, from membership in the 175-member policymaking <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, and first vice chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Military </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>. He had served as premier before he was named party chief in January 1987. <PERSON> Jiang </PERSON>, 62, served as mayor of <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s largest city, from 1985 to 1988, when he moved over to head the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> in the city. He entered the Politburo, where he was a collegue of <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON>'s, in November 1987. The communique said nothing about filing criminal charges against <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON>, who has been accused of supporting a `` counterrevolutionary rebellion.'' The communique acknowledged that <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> `` did something beneficial to the reform, the opening of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> to the outside world and economic work.'' It said the party will `` look further into his case.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> also decided to remove <PERSON> Hu </PERSON> <PERSON> Qili </PERSON>, 60, from the Politburo Standing Committee. <PERSON> Hu </PERSON> is considered a moderate who also opposed the introduction of martial law in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Jiang </PERSON> is a technocrat who speaks Russian and English. In <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION>, he has actively worked to restore the city's reputation as a financial center and to attract foreign investment to revive its industrial base. Some earlier reports had suggested that <PERSON> Qiao </PERSON> <PERSON> Shi </PERSON>, a Politburo member in change of internal security, would be named to replace <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON>. The party also expanded the <ORGANIZATION> Politburo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Standing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> from five to six members, replacing <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> and <PERSON> Hu </PERSON> with <PERSON> Jiang </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Tianjin </LOCATION> Mayor <PERSON> Li </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruihuan </PERSON> and economist <PERSON> Song </PERSON> <PERSON> Ping </PERSON>, head of the party <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. It also announced a reshuffling in the party's four-member Secretariat, removing <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> allies <PERSON> Rui </PERSON> <PERSON> Xingwen </PERSON> and <PERSON> Yan </PERSON> <PERSON> Mingfu </PERSON> and replacing them with <PERSON> Li </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruihuan </PERSON> and Politburo alternate <PERSON> Ding </PERSON> <PERSON> Guangen </PERSON>. The Secretariat is responsible for day-to-day operations. The new Standing Committee members are all regarded as strong advocates of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s open-door economic policies with the outside world. They are also likely to back <PERSON> Deng </PERSON>'s attempt to unify the party behind his hard-line stance toward activists and other critics. The communique said the Politburo met from Monday through Wednesday and the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, which must make all formal decisions on leadership positions, held its session on Friday and today. The leadership changes have been expected since May, when the pro-democracy student demonstrations split the party leadership and triggered a power struggle between moderates and hard-liners. <PERSON> Deng </PERSON>, 84, came down on the side of the hard-liners, deciding to declare martial law in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> on May 20 and ordering the military attack on the city. Earlier today, authorities announced an army propaganda specialist has taken over as editor in chief at the official daily of the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> in a reshuffling of the newspaper's management The foreign affairs office of the <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> said <PERSON> Shao </PERSON> <PERSON> Huaze </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Propaganda </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>, had replaced <PERSON> Tan </PERSON> <PERSON> Wenrui </PERSON> as chief editor of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s leading paper. The office also said <PERSON> Qian </PERSON> <PERSON> Liren </PERSON>, director at the daily, had left his post. He was replaced by <PERSON> Gao </PERSON> <PERSON> Di </PERSON>, a senior official at the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> party </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. Both Qian and <PERSON> Tan </PERSON> resigned because of health reasons, the office said without elaborating. The replacements at T