<HEAD>Revenge of the Lawn: Neighbors in Court Over Heels in Sod</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SOLIHULL, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A woman accused of walking her dog in a sly and vindictive manner across her neighbors' lawn has agreed to pay compensation. `` This is what could be described as a neighbors' dispute that had got out of hand,'' <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> McCann </PERSON>, the prosecuting counsel, told magistrates on Friday. The court in <LOCATION> Solihull </LOCATION>, a suburb of <LOCATION> Birmingham </LOCATION>, heard that <PERSON> Winifred </PERSON> <PERSON> Burrows </PERSON>, 71, and <PERSON> Lillian </PERSON> <PERSON> Priddy </PERSON>, 74, had discovered holes in the lawn bordering their prize-winning garden. Seeking confirmation of their suspicions, they staked out the yard one February night and said they saw <PERSON> Judith </PERSON> <PERSON> Abercrombie </PERSON>, 48, strutting across their grass in high-heeled shoes. When confronted, <PERSON> McCann </PERSON> said, `` Mrs. <PERSON> Abercrombie </PERSON> said to her dog: ` Come on, let's go back and do it again.''' Mrs. <PERSON> Priddy </PERSON> and Mrs. <PERSON> Burrows </PERSON> called the police, who came to Mrs. <PERSON> Abercrombie </PERSON>'s home and asked her to come to the station. `` No chance,'' she allegedly responded and was arrested. `` The prosecution case is that it was an act of intent, it was not an accident or recklessness, and there have been ongoing problems between the two parties,'' <PERSON> McCann </PERSON> said. A charge of causing damage was dismissed when Mrs. <PERSON> Abercrombie </PERSON> agreed to pay 50 pounds -LRB- $ 78 -RRB- compensation to the sisters and to post a bond of 200 pounds -LRB- $ 310 -RRB- to keep the peace for two years. `` I accept there was a confrontation on the night of Feb. 8, but I have always denied, and maintain my denial, that I committed any criminal offense,'' she said afterward. Mrs. <PERSON> Burrows </PERSON> and Mrs. <PERSON> Priddy </PERSON> donated the damages to the Police Benevolent Fund in gratitude for the support of the police. `` We hope this will be the end of the matter,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Priddy </PERSON> said. `` Quite frankly, we feel sorry for her.''
