<HEAD>22 Convicted of Trying to Overthrow Government</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KUWAIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>'s state security court today convicted 22 people of trying to overthrow the government and sentenced them to prison terms ranging from five to 15 years. Another 11 defendants, including a British national of <LOCATION> Lebanese </LOCATION> descent, were acquitted. Most of the defendants belong to the minority Shiite Moslem sect in predominantly Sunni Moslem <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>. The case was first reported when the indictment was released in March, but authorities never said when the defendants tried to overthrow the government. They include 18 Kuwaitis believed to be of Iranian descent, two Iranians, nine Iraqis, two Lebanese, the Briton and one person whose country of origin was unknown. The defendants included engineers, teachers, computer specialists, electricians, laborers and a former police officer. They were charged with belonging to illegal groups that sought `` to demolish the social and economic fabric of the country,'' spread `` destructive ideologies'' and defame the emir, <PERSON> Sheik </PERSON> <PERSON> Jaber </PERSON> <PERSON> al-Ahmed </PERSON> <PERSON> al-Sabah </PERSON>. The indictment said they used public statements and `` writings, sketches and pictures'' in their activities. Only 20 of the defendants appeared before the court during the trial, which began on May 13. Court Chairman <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON> <PERSON> al-Bannai </PERSON> sentenced them during a public session attended by relatives of the defendants. The defendants present smiled broadly but made no comment. <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION> was a repeated target of terrorist attacks during the eight-year Iraq-Iran war. The attacks were blamed on <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, predominately <ORGANIZATION> Shiite </ORGANIZATION> and opposed to <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION> for backing <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>. One case involved an attempt on the life of the emir in May 1985 when a booby-trapped car rammed into his motorcade and exploded. He escaped with minor injuries, but five people were killed. Relations between <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> have improved since a cease-fire in the Iran-Iraq war went into effect in August. But the latest case underscored <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>'s determination to keep monitoring the <ORGANIZATION> Shiite </ORGANIZATION> minority.
