<BYLINE>By DOUG FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWPORT, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Crews worked today to contain 1 million gallons of heating oil that spilled from a tanker and created a five-mile slick that began washing up on the <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> coast. White House officials arrived just hours after the Providence-bound tanker World Prodigy, carrying 7.6 million gallons of heating oil, struck a rock at <LOCATION> Brenton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Reef </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sound </LOCATION> about 4:30 p.m. Friday. Just a few hours later, oil spilled in a collision of an oil tanker and a tugboat at the mouth of the <ORGANIZATION> Houston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ship </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Channel </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Galveston </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. The accidents came three months after nearly 11 million gallons of heavy crude oil gushed into Alaskan waters from the tanker <PERSON> Exxon </PERSON> <PERSON> Valdez </PERSON>, causing the nation's worst oil spill. Army helicopters surveying the <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> shore this morning confirmed that oil was washing ashore near <LOCATION> Jamestown </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bendick </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, director of the state <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Bendick </PERSON> said curiosity seekers in <LOCATION> Jamestown </LOCATION> who were hampering cleanup efforts were removed from the town's picturesque beach, across the harbor from <LOCATION> Newport </LOCATION>. The spill occurred one mile south of <LOCATION> Newport </LOCATION> and by today it was five miles long. No harm to wildlife was immediately reported, but all of the state's beaches were closed today. The <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> said they would remain off-limits until the oil had been cleaned up. Boaters also were asked to stay in port. `` We do n't want boats churning up the oil slick,'' said <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Morin </PERSON>, chief of the department's emergency response team. But the organizers said the Salem Pro Sail Series will continue as scheduled today at the <ORGANIZATION> Newport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Yachting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>. The competition began June 21 and is set to continue until Sunday. Vice Adm. <PERSON> Clyde </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lusk </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> said a team from Mobile, <LOCATION> Ala. </LOCATION>, and special skimmer ships were brought in to combat the spill. Nine of the ship's 27 tanks were damaged, said Coast Guard Capt. <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> of the Marine Safety office in <LOCATION> Providence </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Tim </PERSON> <PERSON> Morgan </PERSON>, a diver who surveyed the hull of the 530-foot tanker, said there is a 200-foot-long gash, as wide as five feet, along one side. There are about 150 feet of dents and smaller holes on the other side, he said. `` The damage is so extreme it's impossible to seal the vessel off with any kind of soft patches,'' <PERSON> Morgan </PERSON> said. The Coast Guard began unloading the World Prodigy about 2:20 a.m., and <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> said the work could take up to a week. Cleanup crews initially strung booms around the slick and later replaced them with booms with deeper skirts to pool the oil, said <PERSON> Lusk </PERSON>. The White House, criticized for its response to the Alaskan spill, reacted swiftly to the <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> accident. President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> dispatched <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Lujan </PERSON> and <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Reilly </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>, to the scene. `` It's a big spill and in a very important place,'' <PERSON> Reilly </PERSON> said at a news conference about 2 a.m. after federal officials met with Gov. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> DiPrete </PERSON>. `` <LOCATION> Narragansett </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> is one of the crown jewels of the country's ocean resources.'' <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Dreedan </PERSON>, a <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> assistant at the scene, said the president has determined to `` do everything possible to respond to this situation,'' adding, `` We've obviously learned something from that situation'' in <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> Providence </LOCATION> port, where the ship sailing under a Greek flag was heading, is about 25 miles from <LOCATION> Newport </LOCATION> via <LOCATION> Narragansett </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION>, which feeds into the <LOCATION> Providence </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Civic </PERSON>, who lives near <LOCATION> Narragansett </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION>, witnessed the accident. `` I'm looking and this guy was barrelling along and boom; he just stopped dead in the water. He was moving pretty good, faster than most,'' he said. Officials said the magnitude was far less than the Valdez disaster in March. The amount was less, and No. 2 heating oil is lighter and easier to recover than the crude oil that poured into Prince <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Sound </PERSON>. `` There still will be a mess on the beach, it still will have to be sucked up with absorbent pads, but at least i