<HEAD>Protest Denounces Expulsion of Ethnic Turks From Bulgaria</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VEDAT ERDAMAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISTANBUL, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 About 150,000 demonstrators today demanded <LOCATION> Bulgaria </LOCATION> end oppression that has led thousands of ethnic Turks to flee <LOCATION> Bulgaria </LOCATION>. The protest in <LOCATION> Taksim </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Square </LOCATION> was organized by the governing <ORGANIZATION> Motherland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and the opposition <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democrat </ORGANIZATION> and True Path Parties. Organizers said thousands of ethnic Turks who immigrated to <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Bulgaria </LOCATION> traveled to <LOCATION> Istanbul </LOCATION> from many western and Thracian cities to attend the rally, which was broadcast live nationally on the state-run television. There were hundreds of red-and-white Turkish flags in the square, and banners hung from surrounding buildings denounced <LOCATION> Bulgaria </LOCATION> and its leader, <PERSON> Todor </PERSON> <PERSON> Zhivkov </PERSON>. Protesters carried banners saying, `` End Bulgarian Cruelty,'' `` Freedom for Turks in <LOCATION> Bulgaria </LOCATION>,'' and `` The New <PERSON> Hitler </PERSON> <PERSON> Zhivkov </PERSON>.'' Political leaders addressing the rally protested the expulsion of ethnic Turks by <LOCATION> Bulgaria </LOCATION>. The crowd chanted slogans such as `` Murderer <PERSON> Zhivkov </PERSON>, army to <LOCATION> Sofia </LOCATION>!'' and `` We want guns against <LOCATION> Bulgaria </LOCATION>!'' In 1984, <LOCATION> Bulgaria </LOCATION> began forcing ethnic Turks to adopt Bulgarian names and forbidding them to speak their language or practice their religion. Thousands of Turks began leaving <LOCATION> Bulgaria </LOCATION> after <PERSON> Zhivkov </PERSON> said May 29 that any Bulgarian citizen, including the 1-million-strong Turkish minority, could leave the country. Three weeks later, 250,000 Turks had applied for passports, and 150,000 of them reportedly received them immediately. In <LOCATION> Istanbul </LOCATION> today, <PERSON> Mumin </PERSON> <PERSON> Gencoglu </PERSON>, the head of the <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Immigrants </ORGANIZATION> from <LOCATION> Bulgaria </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Sevket </PERSON> <PERSON> Yilmaz </PERSON>, chairman of <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION>'s largest labor federation, condemned the Bulgarian oppression and expressed solidarity with ethnic Turks. They said <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> was ready to accept all ethnic Turks who wanted to come, and they called on the international commnuity for support. More than 60,000 ethnic Turks have crossed into <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> over the past month, bringing whatever belongings they could carry. Bulgarian officials say seven people died in violent clashes with security forces in May. But Western diplomats in <LOCATION> Sofia </LOCATION> estimate at least 30 ethnic Turks were killed and up to 5,000 expelled immediately after the clashes. Premier <PERSON> Turgut </PERSON> <PERSON> Ozal </PERSON> has called on <LOCATION> Bulgaria </LOCATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> to guarantee that ethnic Turks who want to leave <LOCATION> Bulgaria </LOCATION> can do so in peace. But <LOCATION> Sofia </LOCATION> rejects a <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> discussion of its Turkish minority, insisting that such an ethnic group no longer exists in <LOCATION> Bulgaria </LOCATION>.
