<TEXT>
 Thousands of people marched through a shopping district to the unofficial <ORGANIZATION> Chinese </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> on Saturday to deliver a petition protesting the crackdown on dissent in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. The two-hour rally and march by at least 5,000 people was the latest expression of anger by this British colony over Communist <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s suppression of the pro-democracy movement. The crackdown, which has included arrests and some executions, has intensified fears over the return of <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> to Chinese rule in 1997. <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> protesters began their demonstration at <LOCATION> Victoria </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION>, where they gathered around a 33-foot-high replica of the `` Goddess of Democracy'' statue, which stood in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>'s Tiananmen Square before the military moved in June 3-4 to disperse pro-democracy demonstrators. After speeches decrying the arrests and executions in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, the crowd marched through the Causeway Bay shopping district to the local <ORGANIZATION> Xinhua </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> office, which is <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>'s representative in the colony. The marchers carried banners that read `` Support the <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> students' long-term struggle,'' `` Down with fascism,'' and `` Down with <PERSON> Li </PERSON> <PERSON> Peng </PERSON>, Long live people power.'' <PERSON> Li </PERSON> <PERSON> Peng </PERSON>, premier of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, is one of the hard-line conservatives behind the suppression of the democracy movement. Leading pro-democracy activists in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> handed a petition calling for the release of all those detained in the crackdown to a <ORGANIZATION> Xinhua </ORGANIZATION> official. The crowd in front of the news agency's building chanted, `` Protest! Protest!'' Several marchers stopped and bowed in front of wreaths placed across the street from the <ORGANIZATION> Xinhua </ORGANIZATION> building in honor of Chinese who have died in the pro-democracy movement.
