<SECOND>AM-Yani the Prodigy,750</SECOND>
<HEAD>Teen-Age Chinese Artist Opens Show at Smithsonian Gallery</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A tranquil world away from the bloody violence in her native <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, 14-year-old artist <PERSON> Wang </PERSON> <PERSON> Yani </PERSON> squatted barefoot on the <LOCATION> Smithsonian </LOCATION> gallery floor and demonstrated with lightning brush and ink strokes why she is called `` a very rare phenomenon anywhere in the world.'' It took the slight, muscular girl in jean shorts slightly more than a half-hour to fill her 8-foot-by-4-foot sheet of paper with pigments and ink, which she dripped, poured, smeared, dabbed and delicately brushed as she danced back and forth. `` In <PERSON> Yani </PERSON>'s hands, the brush sings and the ink dances,'' said one observer. <PERSON> Yani </PERSON> created a scene of two playful black monkeys _ her favorite animals _ gathering pears under the gaze of flitting songbirds and plump, dour hens. She called it `` The Happy Partners In the Orchard,'' stamped it with her name seals in red and shyly smiled for the first time, as the hushed crowd surrounding her in the <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sackler </PERSON> Gallery burst into applause. `` I'm finished,'' she said through an interpreter. `` I'm very happy.'' Her display of extraordinary artistic talent took place at a press briefing last week before a collection of 69 of her paintings goes on display Sunday for a four-month engagement at the <PERSON> Sackler </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Smithsonian </ORGANIZATION> museum of <LOCATION> Asian </LOCATION> art. The show, `` Yani: the <ORGANIZATION> Brush </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Innocence </ORGANIZATION>,'' will appear at the Nelson-Atkins Museum of Art in <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mo. </LOCATION>, from Dec. 16 to Jan. 28 and will be seen at the <LOCATION> Asian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Art </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Museum </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> next March 7 through April 29. The exhibition was organized by the Nelson-Atkins museum and is sponsored by the Chinese Ministry of Culture. The Chinese government's violent crackdown on pro-democracy student demonstrators in the past three weeks did not disrupt plans for the show, as some Sackler officials had feared. <PERSON> Yani </PERSON> and her father flew here from <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> without incident. `` I have not felt there is going to be any effect on <PERSON> Yani </PERSON> in the future,'' said her father, artist <PERSON> Wang </PERSON> <PERSON> Shiqiang </PERSON>, 44. Museum director <PERSON> Milo </PERSON> <PERSON> Beach </PERSON> said <PERSON> Yani </PERSON> is `` a true prodigy'' whose fresh, spontaneous paintings of childlike humor and grace `` have an ability to communicate that is not limited by geography or age.'' She is the youngest artist to be honored with a one-person show in <LOCATION> Smithsonian </LOCATION> history, <PERSON> Beach </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Jan </PERSON> <PERSON> Stuart </PERSON>, a Chinese art expert at the <PERSON> Sackler </PERSON>, said a prodigy of <PERSON> Yani </PERSON>'s gifts in the visual arts is `` a very rare phenomenon anywhere in the world.'' Born in a small village in rural <LOCATION> Guiangxi </LOCATION> province in southern <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Yani </PERSON> started painting when she was 2. Her works were exhibited in three Chinese cities when she was 4, and since have been displayed in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Petersburg </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>. She has turned out an estimated 10,000 paintings, but never had formal art training She said she once took art classes in school, but `` my work was disagreeable to my teacher, so I stopped going.'' Her father, who is an oil painter, has refused to coach <PERSON> Yani </PERSON> and even abandoned his own painting a few years ago to make sure she was not influenced by his own style of Western realism. `` Teaching may spoil her innate creativity,'' he said. `` Nature was her teacher,'' said Ms. <PERSON> Stuart </PERSON>. <PERSON> Yani </PERSON> said she was intrigued by the animals at the local zoo, especially `` the monkeys who are like children playing in kindergarten'' in the mountains and gardens near her home. The exhibition starts with her brush-and-ink portrait of a kitten, done at age 3, and includes a 35-foot handscroll titled `` A Hundred Monkeys'' which she painted at age 9. As she grew older, <PERSON> Yani </PERSON>'s subjects have broadened to include her friends -LRB- `` <PERSON> Yani </PERSON>'s Party'' -RRB-, flowers -LRB- `` The Lotus Flowers Are So Pretty'' -RRB- and landscapes Later, more complex works include `` Last Night I Dreamt I Saw the Racing Egrets.'' Most of <PERSON> Yani </PERSON>'s paintings are stored in her home and none has been sold privately, although 44 of the works that her family gave to the <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> government were sold to collectors, most of them in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, for an undetermined sum. <PERSON> Yani </PERSON>'s father says he was told that four small <PERSON> Yani </PERSON> paintings given to the <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> postal service for a postage stamp design in 1983 were sold to an unknown stamp collector for $ 13,000. <PERSON> Yani </PERSON> will return to the <LOCATION> Sackler </LOCATION> in September to give painting demonstrations for art teachers and school children. She will take her paintings back to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, but may leave an original with the <PERSON> Sackler </PERSON>, a museum spokeswoman said.
