an lands In a 57-page statement issued June 8, <PERSON> Koch </PERSON> said the committee `` unjustly defamed <PERSON> Koch </PERSON> and caused severe damage to its reputation and business.'' The lengthy document reviewed, point by point, the accusations against the 49-year-old oil company, which is based in <LOCATION> Wichita </LOCATION>. It said the figures the committee used in its allegations were inaccurate, and that comparisons with other companies were based on noncomparable statistics. `` The committee stands firmly behind the findings released in its May hearings,'' <PERSON> Hirsch </PERSON> said. `` The committee's investigators caught <PERSON> Koch </PERSON> employees in the act of stealing oil on six separate occasions. `` Koch gaugers and supervisors also admitted to committee investigators that it was company policy to mismeasure oil,'' he said. <PERSON> Hirsch </PERSON> said documents the committee subpoenaed from <LOCATION> Koch </LOCATION> and almost 30 other companies corroborated the committee's findings. He said <PERSON> Koch </PERSON> executives were presented the findings during closed depositions and their responses were cited in the public hearings. `` <PERSON> Koch </PERSON> was also given the opportunity to testify in our public hearings, but they would have been subject, of course, to cross examination by the attorneys who conducted our investigation,'' said <PERSON> Hirsch </PERSON>. Company representatives did not testify at the public hearings. <PERSON> Hirsch </PERSON> said the committee would review <PERSON> Koch </PERSON>'s June 8 statement before making its final report, sometime this fall. The special committee has been investigating all areas of Indian affairs and came upon the <PERSON> Koch </PERSON> case while probing federal agencies assigned to protecting Indian lands. <PERSON> Pearson </PERSON> said the company `` never received a formal, informal, verbal or written invitation'' to testify. When asked if the company requested an opportunity to speak, <PERSON> Pearson </PERSON> said <PERSON> Koch </PERSON> did not feel it would be in its best interest to appear at the hearing because of its format. `` We can be hurt at a hearing,'' he said. `` They -LRB- the committee -RRB- ca n't be.'' In congressional hearings, witnesses usually submit lengthy written statements for the record and then are asked to summarize their comments, followed by questioning from the members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and staff. <PERSON> Pearson </PERSON> said that, unlike in a court of law, those being questioned have limited means to defend themselves and could be greatly damaged if the hearing were televised. In its June 8 statement, <PERSON> Koch </PERSON> said the committee used `` anecdotal evidence which was misleading at best and false at worst'' at the hearing. Of witness <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Limpy </PERSON>, a homeless Cheyenne-Arapaho, <PERSON> Koch </PERSON> said, `` Her problems obviously lie elsewhere and to suggest to this poor lady that <PERSON> Koch </PERSON> is at fault is the height of demagoguery.'' The woman claimed her financial problems stemmed from infrequent, low royalty payments and that the leases on the wells in which she had part interest were sold to <LOCATION> Koch </LOCATION>. `` We heard that the well had been capped for two years, but that someone was stealing our oil because people saw trucks coming and going from the allotment,'' <PERSON> Limpy </PERSON> said in her testimony. <PERSON> Pearson </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Tenneco </ORGANIZATION> owned the leases and <PERSON> Koch </PERSON> bought the oil from <ORGANIZATION> Tenneco </ORGANIZATION>. He said the wells were never capped. He also pointed out that many people had interests in the wells and <PERSON> Limpy </PERSON>'s share was a small fraction of the amount <ORGANIZATION> Tenneco </ORGANIZATION> paid out to those people, explaining her small payments. Two other witnesses, <PERSON> Thurmon </PERSON> <PERSON> Parton </PERSON> and <PERSON> Arnita </PERSON> <PERSON> Parton </PERSON> <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON> testified their royalty checks dropped from $ 3,000 to $ 1,000 a month when <PERSON> Koch </PERSON> became involved with their leases. According to the company's statement, the brother and sister saw an increase in their payments. <PERSON> Koch </PERSON> officials blamed a dissident family member, <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Koch </PERSON>, for the trouble, saying he had a `` vendetta against <ORGANIZATION> Koch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION>.'' One of the witnesses who testified was an investigator who had worked for <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Koch </PERSON>, but a spokesman for <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Koch </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> committee made the first contact. `` In their zeal to get an oil company, and particularly one that was politically unimportant, the staff obviously seized upon the distorted information provided by <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Koch </PERSON>, embellished it with incorrect numbers, and, by withholding or ignoring evidence favorable to <LOCATION> Koch </LOCATION>, produced a totally unfair and one-sided hearing,'' <PERSON> Koch </PERSON> asserted in its statement.
