<HEAD>Senate Finance Committee To Consider Cutting Tax; Making Program
Optional</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release at 5:30 p.m. EDT; time set by source</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sen. <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> said Saturday he will propose cutting the surtax Medicare-eligible Americans pay for the new catastrophic illness insurance, and said the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> also will consider making the program voluntary. Despite opposition from the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration, <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> says he's backing a `` substantial cut'' in the <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> catastrophic so-called supplemental premium that is based on income. The Finance chairman raised the possibility of cutting the tax several months ago if projections of large surpluses in the catastrophic fund were borne out. However, he previously had stopped short of saying he actually would propose a rollback. Enacted less than a year ago, the catastrophic tax has been under heavy fire from many older Americans in upper-income ranges and those who receive catastrophic insurance protection paid by the current or former employers. <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> said the panel will meet in July to consider reducing the tax as well as making catastrophic health care coverage voluntary by linking it to Part B of <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> _ the physician payment program that is financed 75 percent with general federal tax money. Since enacted this year, the catastrophic tax is estimated to produce a surplus of $ 2 billion to $ 4 billion, <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> said. `` I just do n't think that the government ought to be making a profit off of the patients or the beneficiaries of this program, or to use that surplus to try to balance the budget,'' said the <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> Democrat. `` So I've set a hearing for July that will cover these points and to decide whether it should be made voluntary again, and, in turn, I'll be recommending a substantial cut in the premium,'' <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> said. Under the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>'s original plan, beneficiaries would have been able to drop Medicare coverage of physician fees and catastrophic insurance. But by the time the bill was finally approved, the catastrophic coverage was mandatory. <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> has yet to announce his position on the issue of making catastrophic coverage optional. The surtax this year is 15 percent of a Medicare beneficiary's federal income tax of $ 150 or more It is currently estimated that 59 percent of all beneficiaries will pay no supplemental premium in 1989, above the $ 4 basic fee, <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>'s office said. Only 5.6 percent will pay the maximum surtax, set this year at $ 800, <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>'s office said. The surtax is scheduled to be phased in through 1993; by then, it could reach 28 percent of a beneficiary's federal income tax of $ 150 or more. During the five years ending in 1993, the <ORGANIZATION> Congressional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> now estimates, the surtax is likely to bring in about $ 10 billion more than is expected to be paid for catastrophic benefits. But administration officials have cautioned that the surplus may never exist, because the new program of catastrophic drug benefits starting in 1991 could cost far more than previously estimated.
