<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Tiananmen Square has been scrubbed clean of the blood and ashes that stained it the night of June 3-4, when thousands of soldiers crushed student-led protests for a freer society. The only signs of the violence are watchful soldiers brandishing automatic rifles, bullet holes in walls and scars left in the road by marauding army tanks. The burned-out hulks of hundreds of public buses and army trucks have been towed away. New flower beds and freshly painted traffic dividers and garbage bins adorn the 100-acre square, still closed to the public. Many Chinese say it's only window dressing. `` On the surface it's calm, but below that it's very tense,'' said a college student in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> who participated in the demonstrations at <LOCATION> Tiananmen </LOCATION>. `` Many people are worried they might be arrested, like me.'' More than 1,600 have been arrested since the crackdown began, and 27 people have been executed. The government has demonstrated an ability for surveillance never so chillingly revealed in 40 years of communist rule. Television news has shown secretly shot videotapes of people authorities say spied for <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s longtime enemy. Most scenes were of <LOCATION> Tiananmen </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Square </LOCATION>, where the accused were shown watching marches along with hundreds of thousands of other people. The message seemed to be that anybody could be on those tapes, and anybody could be charged with being a counterrevolutionary. Resignation and sullen indifference have replaced the grass-roots fervor that initially stopped the tanks of the <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> from advancing on <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>. Many businesses still are running at half-pace, and much of <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>'s usual `` floating population'' of 1 million peddlers and outsiders looking for work has retreated to the countryside. `` Only about half the normal number of people are here,'' said a sales clerk at the Dongan Market on the normally jammed Wangfujing shopping street. `` Nobody is coming in from the provinces.'' Tibetan merchants who once hawked monkey skulls, tiger and bear paws and other animal parts for medicinal uses outside a foreigner's compound have disappeared Scarlet banners calling for people to support the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and respect the army flutter from hotels, construction cranes and overpasses. A month ago, Westerners in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> were symbols of freedom and hope. `` America is great,'' people would say heartily, flashing thumbs-up signs. `` Your democracy is the best in the world.'' Crowds would part to let foreign journalists see insulting caricatures of Chinese leaders or photograph corpses after the June 3-4 violence, which official <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> reports say killed 200 to 300 people, including many soldiers. Chinese witnesses and Western intelligence sources said the death toll may have been as high as 3,000. An AP reporter who was chased and shot at by two soldiers for photographing marching troops was cheered by a crowd when he emerged from a parking lot where he had been hiding behind a van. Now foreigners are shunned. Commuters wheeling their bicycles past memorials for two soldiers killed in the crackdown edged away uneasily when an American approached. Large signs tell how the two soldiers were thrown off bridges and, when they did n't die, set on fire by angry mobs. Witnesses said one soldier had shot to death a child and the other had shot unarmed adults. `` Please do n't sit here,'' a customer at an all-night restaurant asked a Westerner. `` They see us talking to you and they'll haul us in.'' The proprietor of a nearby restaurant was bolder, inviting an American to sit down and chat. Moments later, a platoon of soldiers marched by and its officer said, `` Get these tables off the sidewalk. They'd better be gone when we come back.'' `` Let them come back, what do we care,'' said the manager. But he moved the tables. Most people have become accustomed to the soldiers, who stare blankly out from under their helmets as they stand guard at street corners or patrol boulevards and back alleys. `` I'm just eating, I do n't care about them,'' said a young man at a restaurant on <LOCATION> Changan </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Avenue </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>'s main thoroughfare. `` They mind their business and I mind mine.'' Newscasts continue to show army officers, workers and even students denouncing the pro-democracy movement, and there are signs the propaganda campaign is working. `` There were a certain number of bad elements on the streets,'' said a 67-year-old man who has been repairing shoes on sidewalks for 50 years. `` The soldiers are n't after me, they're not after you. They're after the evildoers.'' But non-believers are legion. `` Not a single shot was fired in the square, and not one person died there,'' said a hired driver, reciting the government line. `` That's all we're allowed to say.'' Those who were on the streets or within earshot of the thunderous rifle reports of June 3-4 say they will never forget. `` This used to be our square of democracy,'' a college student said, looking across <LOCATION> Tiananmen </LOCATION> toward the Great Hall of the People. `` Now it's their square of dictatorship.''
</TEXT>
