<HEAD>State Board Refuses To Adopt Southern California Smog Plan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A stringent air cleanup plan considered by some a model for the nation has been shelved at least temporarily by state officials who fear it wo n't work unless it gains wider support. The state <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>, citing mistrust between regional air quality officials and business and environmentalist leaders, voted 6-1 Friday to postpone action on the plan for 60 days. `` I'm troubled by the perceptions of this plan I continue to hear from business and local government,'' said <PERSON> Jananne </PERSON> <PERSON> Sharpless </PERSON>, the board's chairwoman. The plan would cut emissions from vehicles, businesses and residences about 80 percent in an effort to make the air in <LOCATION> Southern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> healthy again by 2007. It would also place restrictions on the use of such consumer products as aerosol sprays and barbecue lighter fluids. Officials of the <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Quality </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION>, which encompasses <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> and three counties to the south and west, have estimated the plan would cost $ 2.6 billion a year. Business estimates have placed the cost as high as $ 12 billion. In delaying a vote, the board ordered the district to outline how it plans to account for the costs businesses will face. The board also wants to know how cities and counties will be persuaded to cooperate in enforcement. `` We have to ensure this plan can be implemented,'' Ms. <PERSON> Sharpless </PERSON> said. `` We want a plan that works.'' If adopted by the state board, appointed by Gov. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Deukmejian </PERSON>, the plan also would require approval from the federal <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>. Ms. <PERSON> Sharpless </PERSON>, who is <PERSON> Deukmejian </PERSON>'s environmental affairs secretary, said the governor did not advise her to reject the plan, but said he wanted the concerns of business better addressed. `` The governor is concerned about the impact on the economy,'' she said.
