<SECOND>AM-Rocky Flats' Neighbors, Bjt,0882</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wary Residents Await Outcome of Rocky Flats Probe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SANDY SHORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Residents of <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION>'s northern suburbs are co-existing a little more uneasily with Rocky Flats nuclear weapons plant these days, but say an investigation at the facility is cause for concern, not hysteria. `` We're all concerned, naturally,'' said <PERSON> Omar </PERSON> <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON>, who has lived and worked in <LOCATION> Arvada </LOCATION> for 23 years. `` What are you going to do? As a citizen you just hold your breath and hope for the best.'' `` We're not panicky by any means,'' said <PERSON> Earl </PERSON> <PERSON> McGuire </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Broomfield </LOCATION>. `` We are mad for the simple reason that I think we're being lied to. The investigation was made public June 6 when 75 <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> agents raided the plant 16 miles northwest of <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION>. The on-scene inquiry wound up last week. Authorities have said it will take at least six months to analyze the evidence collected during the two-week search. An affidavit filed in <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> alleges that hazardous wastes were burned illegally in a plant incinerator and were dumped late last year into creeks feeding into water supplies for <LOCATION> Broomfield </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Westminster </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Thornton </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Northglenn </LOCATION>. A group of 16 anti-nuclear and peace organizations has demanded that Gov. <PERSON> Roy </PERSON> <PERSON> Romer </PERSON> close the plant. Other groups, such as the <ORGANIZATION> Denver </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION>, supported <PERSON> Romer </PERSON>'s successful effort to give the state authority to more strictly monitor the plant, which is under federal contract. The probe has had little visible effect on day-to-day life in the nearby suburbs of <LOCATION> Broomfield </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Westminster </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Arvada </LOCATION>, where 155,000 of metropolitan <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION>'s roughly 1.6 million residents live. But people in those suburbs are concerned, particularly about the safety of their water, city leaders and residents say. Sales of bottled and distilled water systems are up. `` My gut feeling is that the people in <LOCATION> Broomfield </LOCATION> have accepted it and the city has been very responsive,'' said <PERSON> Marty </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, editor of the weekly <ORGANIZATION> Broomfield </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enterprise </ORGANIZATION> newspaper. `` I'm getting more letters over an animal impound issue we have here than over Rocky Flats.'' `` We've been in <LOCATION> Broomfield </LOCATION> since 1964 and we've known Rocky Flats has been there all along,'' said resident <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON>. `` Our water supply is always in jeopardy because we are so close to it. `` I really expected a lot more panic,'' he said. `` Everybody is concerned; everybody knows Rocky Flats is there. Let's make sure we know what they're doing there and let's clean it up.'' `` I think there's a group that certainly is concerned about the overall environmental safety, taking a wait-and-see attitude to see what the investigation will produce,'' said Westminster City Manager <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON>. `` There also is a silent element that is not expressing concern, not jumping up and down, not demanding the closure of the plant, not very concerned with what's been in the media. `` There also is a very small vociferous group that is demanding the closure of the plant, and we've heard from those people for the last few years,'' he said. Established in the early 1950s, the plant _ a large complex of buildings surrounded by a buffer zone, the whole site covering 11 square miles _ manufactures triggers for nuclear weapons. It has been a source of controversy in the metropolitan area for two decades. Whenever public safety concerns surfaced, the federal government reassured the public that the facility posed no health threat. A wave of concern erupted in 1957, when a fire and explosion in a plutonium-reprocessing building released an undetermined amount of plutonium into the atmosphere; and again in 1969 when a fire caused about $ 70 million in damage. In the 1970s, then-Jefferson County Health Director Dr. <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> began studies of the plant's impact. He later published papers in which he claimed the cancer rate among nearby residents shot up in the 1960s and 1970s. Today, about 5,000 people work at the plant, and many live in the nearby towns, which were established primarily as bedroom communities. Recently, the towns have taken steps to attract business and industry and diversify their economic base. The plant is managed by <ORGANIZATION> Rockwell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> for the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION>. The news of the latest investigation initially triggered hundreds of calls to the <LOCATION> Broomfield </LOCATION> city offices, which opened a hotline to reassure citizens that tests proved the water was safe. But a week or so later, no one addressed the issue during a city council meeting. <PERSON> McGuire </PERSON> said he purchased bottled water after learning of the alleged contamination, but his family is returning to tap water because of uncertainty over what type of elements are in bottled water. <PERSON> Laurie </PERSON> <PERSON> Kappler </PERSON>, who has lived in <LOCATION> Broomfield </LOCATION> for five years, and has drunk tap water during that time, said, `` It's not going to make a difference to buy bottled water now.'' `` As far as what has happened, we will probably go on living our lives the same way as before,'' said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Broomfield </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION>. `` As far as business and economic development is concerned, the damage has been done. `` We're not born with four arms out here,'' he said. `` This is not a war zone.''
