cceeding the late <PERSON> Hu </PERSON> <PERSON> Yaobang </PERSON>. Hu, another <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> protege, was purged following accusations that he was soft on student demonstrations. <PERSON> Hu </PERSON>'s death April 15 triggered the latest round of demonstrations. <PERSON> Jiang </PERSON>, a university graduate who spent time in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> in the 1950s and speaks Russian and English, served as electronics industry minister and in various other technical posts before being named mayor of <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION> in 1985. He relinquished that position to become <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION> party secretary last year. Like <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON>, he is comfortable around foreigners and has backed <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s open-door policy by working to attract foreign investment to help revitalize <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION>'s antiquated industrial base. Politically, however, he is considered a hard-liner. During the student protests he tried to censor <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Herald </ORGANIZATION>, then <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s most liberal newspaper, and he moved quickly to stifle unrest in <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION> that followed the military crackdown in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Jiang </PERSON> is believed to be the son-in-law of <PERSON> Li </PERSON> <PERSON> Xiannian </PERSON>, a former president and one of the Old Guard hard-liners who rallied behind <PERSON> Deng </PERSON>'s decision to suppress the student movement with force. <PERSON> Jiang </PERSON> also joined the <ORGANIZATION> Politburo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Standing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, which was expanded from five to six members. Replacing <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> and <PERSON> Hu </PERSON> <PERSON> Qili </PERSON> were <PERSON> Jiang </PERSON>, <LOCATION