<FIRST>r a AM-BrothersShot     06-24 0481</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brothers Shot,0494</SECOND>
<HEAD>Before Killing Himself, Boy Called Shooting `a Nightmare'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JANESVILLE, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Before turning the gun on himself, a 14-year-old boy wrote a note to his mother saying that shooting his 12-year-old brother to death was `` a nightmare,'' authorities say. `` Mom, I accidentally shot Clay. It's a nightmare, so I killed myself,'' read the note that <PERSON> Damien </PERSON> <PERSON> Bienash </PERSON> left on the back of a cash register receipt on the dining room table. The one-line statement was found when the boys' mother, <PERSON> Judy </PERSON> <PERSON> Bienash </PERSON>, 36, returned home Thursday afternoon and found the bodies of her sons <PERSON> Damien </PERSON> and <PERSON> Clay </PERSON>. Police and <LOCATION> Rock </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>'s chief deputy coroner, <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Messner </PERSON>, concluded that the deaths were a murder-suicide although friends and relatives of the victims disputed the notion. Authorities said a quarrel over baseball cards may have led <PERSON> Damien </PERSON> to shoot his younger brother with a gun that had been a gift to the older boy from his father. `` There are only two people who could tell us why it happened, and they are both dead,'' Police Lt. <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Loveland </PERSON> said. But <PERSON> Christine </PERSON> <PERSON> Dunham </PERSON>, an aunt, said Friday that the incident `` was an accident, a total accident. It is not like them at all. They loved each other too dearly. They always looked out for each other.'' According to police reports, <PERSON> Clay </PERSON> was shot `` basically square in the face,'' indicating the shot from <PERSON> Damien </PERSON> may have been aimed. A knife was found near <PERSON> Clay </PERSON>'s right hand, and there were signs, including a large fan that was tipped over, that indicated there may have been a struggle, <PERSON> Messner </PERSON> said. A number of baseball cards were found on the floor near <PERSON> Clay </PERSON>'s feet Police said the boys were quarreling over baseball cards before their mother left earlier in the day. `` Clay, apparently, was an avid baseball card collector,'' <LOCATION> Loveland </LOCATION> said, `` and <PERSON> Damien </PERSON> grabbed a handful of them. That may not have been the cause -LRB- of the shooting -RRB-, but that's the last thing the mother saw.'' `` Apparently they had had altercations off and on,'' <PERSON> Messner </PERSON> said. `` I think they were awfully good kids, but had altercations a little more often than normal.'' <PERSON> Messner </PERSON> said a single-shot, 20-gauge shotgun, a gift to <PERSON> Damien </PERSON> from his father, was used in the shootings. The parents are divorced. The boys' aunt said the boy had taken a hunter safety course. The deaths, coupled with a shooting in <LOCATION> Milwaukee </LOCATION> on Thursday evening in which a boy critically wounded a friend while playing with a gun, led to renewed calls at the state Capitol for a Florida-style gun law. The law passed last week in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> after a spate of child shootings there imposes penalties on adults who allow loaded weapons to come into the hands of children and allows authorities to prosecute the adult for a felony if a child's play with a weapon results in death or injury.
