<HEAD>Jiang is Liberal on Economic Reforms, Against Political Change</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Jiang </PERSON> <PERSON> Zemin </PERSON>, the new leader of the world's largest <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, has been a leader in efforts to open <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s economy to the world, but he opposes political reform <PERSON> Jiang </PERSON>, 62, on Saturday was named general secretary of the 47-million-member <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. He replaces <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> <PERSON> Ziyang </PERSON>, who was ousted in disgrace for expressing sympathy for the pro-democracy movement. <PERSON> Jiang </PERSON>'s selection to the nation's most powerful post came as a surprise to many <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> watchers. Although he has the experience and the right political stance for the job, he lacks a power base. `` His base is his popularity, but in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> that's not enough,'' said one Chinese source in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> who is familiar with <PERSON> Jiang </PERSON>'s family `` He has no organizations behind him, like the military or the state security organs. `` If the senior leaders want him to do something, he'll have no choice.'' <PERSON> Jiang </PERSON> has been party secretary of <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s largest city, and a member of the 17-member Politburo, the party's top decision-making body. From 1985 until last year he was mayor of <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION>, aggressively promoting it as a financial and foreign investment center and tackling the daunting transportation and housing problems of the city of 12 million. `` <PERSON> Jiang </PERSON> is politically hard-line and economically liberal,'' said the Chinese source. `` He likes good food and dresses well, too. He is very smooth, very suave, a likable man.'' Among the joint ventures <PERSON> Jiang </PERSON> has brought to his city are the <ORGANIZATION> Shanghai </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hilton </ORGANIZATION>, one of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s most luxurious hotels. He has also worked with <PERSON> Prescott </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, brother of President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, to establish a golf course in <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION>, the source said. <PERSON> Jiang </PERSON> made an impressive showing last month when he played host to Soviet President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> during <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s visit to the city. The two talked about economic reforms. `` He has a combination of suaveness but also a history of managing difficult situations that undoubtedly recommended him for this job,'' said <PERSON> Lynn </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON>, an instructor at <ORGANIZATION> Princeton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> and visiting scholar at the University of <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, who spent the second half of 1988 in <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION>. <PERSON> White </PERSON> said <PERSON> Jiang </PERSON> lost some popularity among <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION> citizens for `` representing <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> at least as well as he represented them,'' and for his recent moves against the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Herald </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s most liberal newspaper before it was shut down in May <PERSON> Jiang </PERSON> moved swiftly to arrest protesters and quell demonstrations that broke out in <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION> after the military crackdown in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> on June 3-4. The first Chinese condemned for participating in the protest movement were three <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION> men who were executed Wednesday. The Chinese source said <PERSON> Jiang </PERSON> was supported by his two relatively liberal predecessors, <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> and the late <PERSON> Hu </PERSON> <PERSON> Yaobang </PERSON>, and has always had a good relationship with intellectuals. His ties with <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> and intellectuals were strained, however, after <PERSON> Jiang </PERSON> moved to censor the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Herald </ORGANIZATION> and its editor <PERSON> Qin </PERSON> <PERSON> Benli </PERSON>, the source said. <PERSON> Jiang </PERSON> was born in July 1926 in <LOCATION> Yangzhou </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, near <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION>, and joined the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> in 1946. A year later he graduated from the <ORGANIZATION> Electrical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Machinery </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jiaotong </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION>. He worked as a trainee at an automobile factory in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> in 1955, then returned to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> the next year to become deputy chief engineer for dynamic mechanics at a plant in northeastern <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and deputy director of the <ORGANIZATION> Shanghai </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electrical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Equipment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Jiang </PERSON>, like most bureaucrats of his generation, apparently was purged from office during the 1966-76 Cultural Revolution. He reappeared in 1980 as a senior official in the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> on Import and Export Affairs and the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZA