<HEAD>Police Raid University Campus, Arrest Student Protesters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Riot troopers backed by fire trucks raided a university campus before dawn Saturday and arrested 21 students accused of organizing violent anti-government protests, police said. Police said about 3,500 riot police searched two buildings at <ORGANIZATION> Hanyang </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in eastern <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> for student leaders. At least 21 students were arrested, but many more escaped before police arrived, police said. Police said hundreds of firebombs and clubs were seized. Radical students, a powerful minority on campuses, have used the <LOCATION> Hanyang </LOCATION> campus as a stronghold of anti-government protests. Also Saturday, in the southern provincial capital of <LOCATION> Kwangju </LOCATION>, news reports said about 400 radical students armed with firebombs and steel bars attacked prosecutors' offices, burning two cars and injuring five policemen. The attackers briefly occupied the compound of a three-story building housing prosecutors' offices and fled after shattering windows of the building and 16 cars, the reports said. Police arrested three students. One student was seriously injured when he jumped off the top of the building, shouting slogans denouncing the government, said <PERSON> Yonhap </PERSON>, the South Korean news agency. Police have raided university campuses in recent weeks to arrest radical students leaders. About 500 dissidents and radicals have been arrested and sent to jail so far this year. The dissidents are demanding the fall of the government of President <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> Tae-woo and the withdrawal of the 43,000 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> troops in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>. They say the American presence hampers reconciliation with communist <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>.
