<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BURLINGTON, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 At age 81 she may have thought she had seen everything, but <PERSON> Dale </PERSON> <PERSON> Granzeau </PERSON> ran into something new when she encountered a squirrel swimming in her toilet. The animal apparently ended a fall down a plumbing vent Friday by swimming through a waste pipe and bobbing up in the toilet bowl about the same time Mrs. <PERSON> Granzeau </PERSON> was stirring from a night's sleep. `` I screamed and ran out and shut the door,'' she said. `` I had hysterics. I'm still shaking about it.'' When all other explanations for finding a squirrel in the toilet were exhausted, police concluded the animal fell into the roof vent pipe, said Sgt. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Kubath </PERSON>. `` Sometimes I do n't even open my eyes when I get up in the morning. Can you imagine finding this?'' asked <PERSON> Eileen </PERSON> <PERSON> Butler </PERSON>, a manager at <LOCATION> Bruesewitz </LOCATION>, a local plumbing contractor where workers said they had heard of such mishaps before. <PERSON> Marvin </PERSON> <PERSON> McCray </PERSON> said he'd never seen anything like it. The 22-year veteran of the <ORGANIZATION> Racine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Humane </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> was called to net the 3-month-old squirrel, which he released outside. `` I do n't think he'll be trying that again,'' <PERSON> McCray </PERSON> said. <PERSON> McCray </PERSON> said he's seen just about every animal come down a fireplace, including ducks, hawks, raccoons and squirrels, but an animal swimming up the toilet was a new one for him. Mrs. <PERSON> Granzeau </PERSON> said she already had contacted a plumber to put a screen over the vent pipe. `` I hope I never see this again,'' she said. `` What a bad start for the day.''
