<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When a dolphin appeared in <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>, the locals, understandably, got concerned. `` I think it's going to die,'' fretted <PERSON> Vincent </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON>, 15, as he stared down into the murky waters. `` The only thing you see in here is garbage ... cars and shopping carts.'' The shoreline at East 96th Street was filled Friday with police, journalists and concerned citizens, all peering off-shore. `` I called 911,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Soto </PERSON>, 41, who lives nearby. `` I'd hate to see a dolphin get killed by these speedboats and Circle Line boats. Those who know say the dolphin seemed to be doing just fine. One expert said the visitor can easily dodge boats as long as its sonar is working. And <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> Garibaldi </PERSON>, director of the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aquarium </LOCATION>, figures the dolphin is contentedly feasting on marine munchies such as black bass and herring, which also -LRB- yes, it's true -RRB- live in the waterway. <PERSON> Garibaldi </PERSON> said a staff member came to the area Wednesday when the dolphin was first reported sighted. `` It looks like it's most likely a whitesided dolphin,'' he said. `` It appears in good health and has no trouble swimming.'' His staff advised police and others to leave the dolphin alone, and he noted that harassment of a marine mammal is against federal law. A woman who answered the phone at the aquarium Saturday said that officials there are monitoring the dolphin, but she was n't sure if they had seen it Saturday.
