<BYLINE>By KATHY GANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> chief <PERSON> Yasser </PERSON> <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> on Saturday offered to mediate a political solution to the civil war in neighboring <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, a guerrilla leader said. After a 30-minute meeting with <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> at <LOCATION> Islamabad </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>, guerrilla leader <PERSON> Gulbadin </PERSON> <PERSON> Hekmatyar </PERSON> said the provisional government established by the insurgents will vote on <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON>'s offer. <PERSON> Hekmatyar </PERSON> is foreign minister of the government, which the U.S.-backed Moslem guerrillas plan to install in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> if they oust the Marxist government. <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> later told <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION>, `` I have discussed with all the parties to this conflict our own initiative.'' He did not elaborate. A spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> said earlier that <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> supported a neutral government made up of technocrats and independent of the communists or the Moslem insurgents. In the past, guerrilla leaders have rejected the neutral government proposal. But the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> representative in <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Ahmad </PERSON> <PERSON> Abdul </PERSON> <PERSON> Razzaq </PERSON> <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Salman </PERSON>, said: `` It is very important that they change their views.'' The guerrillas began fighting in 1978 after the communists took over in a coup. Soviet forces entered <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> a year later to bolster the communist government and stayed for nine years. <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> completed the withdrawal of its troops in February. `` The Soviets are gone,'' said <PERSON> Ahmed </PERSON> <PERSON> Abdul </PERSON> <PERSON> Karim </PERSON> <PERSON> Elhih </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> consul general in <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>. `` The reason to fight is over.'' However, the guerrillas, who have headquarters in <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, say the war will continue until they oust the Afghan government. They have refused to negotiate with President <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> and his <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. In a release issued late Saturday by the guerrilla-controlled <ORGANIZATION> Afghan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Hekmatyar </PERSON> said he told <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> the Soviets should stop supporting <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> and sending weapons to his forces. `` I also told him that the mujahedeen do not accept the idea of sharing power with <PERSON> Najib </PERSON>,'' <PERSON> Hekmatyar </PERSON> said. But <PERSON> Elhih </PERSON> said the insurgents should relent. `` Why not talk to your enemies? If you have courage to fight, you should have courage to talk,'' he said. He said both sides had approached <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> about mediating and that the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> leader met earlier with representatives of <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> and the guerrillas. <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON>, who was welcomed at the airport by Prime Minister <PERSON> Benazir </PERSON> <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON>, previously visited <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> in March. Then, he laid the cornerstone for a <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Embassy </LOCATION> and met with guerrilla leaders. Guerrilla sources said at the time that the meeting accomplished little. <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> urged the