<HEAD>Instruments Show No Stress As Crippled Vessel Moves Into Open Water</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Oil Spill, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL JENKINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VALDEZ, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The damaged tanker <PERSON> Exxon </PERSON> <PERSON> Valdez </PERSON> was towed Saturday through the often stormy Gulf of <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, but there was no sign of stress at critical points and no significant dribbling of residual oil near the ship. The 897-foot tanker ran aground three months ago on <LOCATION> Bligh </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Reef </LOCATION>, ripping large gashes in its hull and releasing nearly 11 million gallons of heavy North Slope crude oil into Prince <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Sound </PERSON>, causing the nation's worst oil spill. The vessel was refloated two weeks after the accident and towed 25 miles to an already soiled anchorage near <LOCATION> Naked </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>. There, divers and salvage crews made it seaworthy for the 2,500-mile trip to a <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION> shipyard where it is scheduled for $ 25 million in repairs. Two ocean-going tugs began towing the huge tanker out of <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> waters early Friday. The procession was halted about four hours Friday night for a final <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> inspection before leaving the Hinchinbrook Entrance and proceeding into open water, officials said. `` The strain gauges aboard the vessel showed no stress,'' <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Tucker </PERSON>, an Exxon spokesman in <LOCATION> Valdez </LOCATION>, said Saturday. `` There was no trace of oil on or near the boat.'' Observers who earlier had watched the procession lift anchor under gray and gloomy skies reported a light film of oil trailing the virtually empty tanker. But the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> released a statement prepared by <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> that generally discounted the seriousness of those observations. A light sheen was observed coming off the <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Valdez </ORGANIZATION> `` for a few minutes after the ship's departure,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Brenda </PERSON> <PERSON> Toledo </PERSON>, who quoted from the statement. It was believed that most of that sheen was a `` bio-mass,'' microorganisms or algae, `` plus an insignificant'' amount of oil that washed out of the open tanks during turbulence as the vessel got under way, the statement said. The sheen was very thin _ too thin for skimmer boats to pick up, officials said. Some of it was recovered by absorbant pads, officials said. `` The <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> has said this was not considered serious and not unexpected,'' <PERSON> Toledo </PERSON> read. `` All discharge has stopped,'' she said. `` There has been none since the initial startup.'' The vessels have been moving at about 6 knots and were to slow to an average speed of 5 knots as they continue toward <LOCATION> Southern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, officials said.
