<HEAD>Blade Device Used to Slice Away Plaque From Clogged Heart Artery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A tiny rotating blade device was inserted surgically and used to slice away plaque to unclog a patient's heart artery in a first-of-its-kind procedure, a doctor at <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Luke </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> said. Cardiologist <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Cummins </PERSON> said <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Alfson </PERSON>, 58, was the first patient in medical history to undergo an atherectomy, in which an experimental blade device is used to clear plaque from a blocked heart artery. <PERSON> Cummins </PERSON> said he inserted the tiny blade device, which was attached to a long tube, into an artery in the patient's leg and maneuvered it carefully to the heart. The rotating blade sliced away the plaque, which was then sucked out of the artery by a vacuum attached to the device. The procedure successfully restored blood flow to <PERSON> Alfson </PERSON>'s heart, <ORGANIZATION> Cummins </ORGANIZATION> said. `` The hope is that if you actually remove the plaque from the artery, it wo n't narrow down again,'' <PERSON> Cummins </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Alfson </PERSON> said he had bypass surgery 10 years ago and a vein from his leg was grafted to the heart. Since then he has twice undergone angioplasty _ the use of a balloon to open the clogged blood vessel. <PERSON> Alfson </PERSON> said the experimental atherectomy took about two hours Friday and was relatively painless. He remained hospitalized Saturday, but the <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Luke </ORGANIZATION>'s declined to release a condition report.
