<HEAD>Illinois Legislature Votes To Repeal Premarital AIDS Tests</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRI COLBY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The nation's only law requiring AIDS testing for a marriage license needs only Gov. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON>'s signature to be off the books The Legislature sent a repeal measure to <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON>'s desk on a 33-23 <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> vote late Friday. A spokesman for <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> said the governor had not decided whether to sign the bill, which was approved in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> last month on a 65-48 vote. Sen. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Marovitz </PERSON>, the bill's sponsor, said that <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>, the only other state to have adopted such a law, already had repealed its statute. He also noted that such groups as the <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> were opposed to the testing requirement. `` This is a low-risk population,'' <PERSON> Marovitz </PERSON> said, referring to couples applying for marriage licenses. The state <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> said that through mid-June, 44 people had tested positive for exposure to the AIDS-causing virus out of an estimated 221,000 marriage-license applicants who have been tested since the requirement started in January 1988. `` This is not good public health policy,'' <PERSON> Marovitz </PERSON> said. `` The key to this disease is education, getting people to come in voluntarily and be tested.'' `` There's nothing in the law, should we pass this bill, that will bar someone from having an AIDS test,'' he said. Critics countered that the premarital tests help monitor the spread of acquired immune deficiency syndrome and reduce the chance of children getting the disease even though those testing positive for the AIDS virus can still marry. `` That child is an innocent and we have a right to protect the children,'' said Sen. <PERSON> Adeline </PERSON> <PERSON> Geo-Karis </PERSON>. `` You eliminate the testing program, you eliminate public awareness,'' said Sen. <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Schaffer </PERSON>. `` I think we ought to keep the test going. Frankly, I hope it never shows up a lot of positives.'' The measure would also repeal the requirement that couples be tested for syphilis before getting married. A study by public health officials estimated that the cost that engaged couples had to pay for testing and associated doctors' visits was about $ 2.5 million over six months last year, or $ 312,000 for each of the eight cases of infection identified during that period The authors of the study also noted that the state was losing thousands of dollars in revenue becauses <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> couples were traveling to neighboring states to get married to avoid paying for the AIDS tests.
