<HEAD>Collision Spills Oil from Barge in Houston Ship Channel</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to CORRECT that barge sted tug collided
with cargo vessel, UPDATE with barge emptied and removed, ship channel
reopened, quote on outlook for cleanup. Picks up 11th graf, `Kennedy said....'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Oil Spill, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LA PORTE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> and cleanup crews battled strong wind and rough water Saturday to survey and try to contain a 250,000-gallon oil spill from a barge ruptured in a collision in the <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> Ship Channel. The winds of more than 15 mph with higher gusts prevented workers from surrounding the barge with containment booms until late morning, Chief Petty Officer <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> said. He said the Panamanian-registered motor vessel Rachel-B collided around 6:20 p.m. Friday with one of three barges being driven by a tugboat owned by Coastal Towing. Investigators have not determined who was at fault for the accident. The collision ruptured and emptied three of 12 tanks on one of the barges, and each tank was holding about 2,000 barrels or 84,000 gallons of heavy crude oil, <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> said. The first major oil spill in eight years in the ship channel came just a few hours after 1 million gallons of heating oil spilled from a tanker off <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>. After the remaining oil was pumped out of the damaged barge and it was towed away Saturday, authorities reopened eight miles of the channel they had closed from the area where it begins running inland to <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> from upper <LOCATION> Galveston </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION>. The 40-foot-deep channel continues through the bay southeast to <LOCATION> Galveston </LOCATION>, on the Gulf of <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. The accident occurred in the bay where the ship channel intersects with the <LOCATION> Bayport </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Channel </LOCATION>, as the tug headed inland and the other vessel, a tanker whose cargo was not determined, headed outbound, officials said. The tug operator, fearing a worse spill if the barge overturned, maneuvered it after the accident out of the deep channel until it was grounded in shallow water, official said. When the weather finally allowed a <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> helicopter flight late Saturday morning, the aerial look showed the slick stretching two miles to the <LOCATION> Galveston </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> shoreline between Red Bluff and the <LOCATION> Bayport </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Channel </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> said. It was nearly continuous and about a mile wide at its widest point, he said. The barge owner hired a contractor, <ORGANIZATION> Garner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION>, to contain and clean up the spill, <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> said. Workers laid booms around the barge and also to direct the flow of the spill away from shore and into the <LOCATION> Bayport </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Channel </LOCATION>. `` It looks pretty good at this point. If we can get it contained within <LOCATION> Bayport </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Channel </LOCATION>, it should be fairly easy to clean up,'' <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> said. `` Some of the slick is already being driven into that area by the winds and rains, so they're just trying to funnel it all in.'' <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> said there had been no reports of damage to fish and wildlife. `` Fortunately this is an area of the bay where there are not many environmentally sensitive areas,'' he said, adding that the flow of the spill apparently did not endanger shrimp grounds or oyster beds in the bay. The last major spill in <LOCATION> Galveston </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> occurred in 1981 when the Olympic Gloria dumped about 7,000 barrels of oil after a collision with a tanker.
