<HEAD>Snoopy Meets Jazz At New York Jazz Festival</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RAEBURN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Wynton </PERSON> <PERSON> Marsalis </PERSON> woke his band up early Saturday, even though they had played a late show the night before to help kick off this year's JVC Jazz Festival. <PERSON> Marsalis </PERSON> had an important piece of business to take care of Saturday afternoon. He was passing on the tradition. In a delightful program called `` Cooling It With Snoopy,'' <PERSON> Marsalis </PERSON> used his trumpet to entertain a theater full of children, giving both the kids and their parents plenty to enjoy. <PERSON> Marsalis </PERSON> has won wide acclaim for his jazz recordings and performances. He has carved out a second career as a classical artist. All the time he has maintained yet another career, less celebrated but perhaps likely to have as much or more impact as his performances. That's <PERSON> Wynton </PERSON> <PERSON> Marsalis </PERSON> the teacher. He devotes much of his time to clinics for student musicians at all levels. Saturday he looked out at an audience whose members were mostly too young to have begun music lessons. His job was to give them the bug _ get them interested. Snoopy paraded down the center aisle of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s Town Hall theater as <PERSON> Marsalis </PERSON>, members of his regular group and a few friends played the familiar theme from the Peanuts television specials. Then <PERSON> Marsalis </PERSON> explained to Snoopy how a jazz band was put together. The bass walks. `` The drums in a jazz band are like the motor in a car,'' he said. `` It gives it the energy, the drive.'' The saxophone, trumpet, trombone and clarinet can be mournful, happy, wild and restrained, <PERSON> Marsalis </PERSON> explained _ and the musicians demonstrated. <PERSON> Marsalis </PERSON> had the audience counting the four beats in a jazz shuffle, the three beats of a waltz and the 12 measures in the blues. One of the highlights was the performance of 13-year-old <PERSON> Amani </PERSON> <PERSON> A.W </PERSON>. <PERSON> Murray </PERSON> on alto sax and 12-year-old <PERSON> Jason </PERSON> <PERSON> Marsalis </PERSON>, <PERSON> Wynton </PERSON>'s brother, on drums `` I want you to hear how kids play jazz,'' <PERSON> Wynton </PERSON> said. In the case of these two, kids play jazz amazingly well. Judging by the audience's reaction to <LOCATION> Marsalis </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Snoopy </PERSON> and host <PERSON> Murray </PERSON> <PERSON> Horwitz </PERSON>, director of cultural affairs programming at <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION>, the concert was a whopping success.
