h old growth is remaining. The timber industry maintains there are 7.5 million acres of old growth in <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>; the <ORGANIZATION> Wilderness </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> says it is more like 2.1 million acres. `` Is there any way we can get these groups together to stipulate with some kind of consistency?'' <PERSON> Hatfield </PERSON> asked. During the meeting, <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Tuttle </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> director of the <ORGANIZATION> Wilderness </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION>, agreed to closely examine millions of acres of timberlands that lie between the old growth estimates in an effort to help free up some timber for immediate use. <PERSON> Goldschmidt </PERSON> challenged whether environmentalists were truly willing to compromise. `` Is it really possible for you folks to engage in a serious discussion of timber supply?'' <PERSON> Goldschmidt </PERSON> asked. `` You keep taking away from the base.'' The meeting was called by <PERSON> Goldschmidt </PERSON>, Rep. <PERSON> Les </PERSON> <PERSON> AuCoin </PERSON>, D-Ore., and <PERSON> Hatfield </PERSON>, R-Ore The wood products industry is the biggest single industry in <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>.
